# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wind-turbine-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] In aeronautics, blade pitch refers to the angle of the blades of an aircraft propeller or helicopter rotor.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch is measured relative to the aircraft body.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] It is usually described as "fine" or "low" for a more vertical blade angle, and "coarse" or "high" for a more horizontal blade angle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch is normally described as a ratio of forward distance per rotation assuming no slip.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch acts much like the gearing of the final drive of a car.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Low pitch yields good low speed acceleration (and climb rate in an aircraft) while high pitch optimizes high speed performance and fuel economy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] It is quite common for an aircraft to be designed with a variable-pitch propeller, to give maximum thrust over a larger speed range.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] A fine pitch would be used during take-off and landing, whereas a coarser pitch is used for high-speed cruise flight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] This is because the effective angle of attack of the propeller blade decreases as airspeed increases.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] To maintain the optimum effective angle of attack, the pitch must be increased.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch angle is not the same as blade angle of attack.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] As speed increases, blade pitch is increased to keep blade angle of attack constant.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] A propeller blade's "lift", or its thrust, depends on the angle of attack combined with its speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Because the velocity of a propeller blade varies from the hub to the tip, it is of twisted form in order for the thrust to remain approximately constant along the length of the blade; this is called "blade twist".
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] This is typical of all but the crudest propellers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] In helicopters, pitch control changes the angle of incidence of the rotor blades, which in turn affects the blades' angle of attack.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Main rotor pitch is controlled by both collective and cyclic, whereas tail rotor pitch is altered using pedals.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Feathering the blades of a propeller means to increase their angle of pitch by turning the blades to be parallel to the airflow.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] This minimizes drag from a stopped propeller following an engine failure in flight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Some propeller-driven aircraft permit the pitch to be decreased beyond the fine position until the propeller generates thrust in the reverse direction.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] This is called thrust reversal, and the propeller position is called the beta position.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch control is a feature of nearly all large modern horizontal-axis wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] It is used to adjust the rotation speed and the generated power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] While operating, a wind turbine's control system adjusts the blade pitch to keep the rotor speed within operating limits as the wind speed changes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Feathering the blades stops the rotor during emergency shutdowns, or whenever the wind speed exceeds the maximum rated speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] During construction and maintenance of wind turbines, the blades are usually feathered to reduce unwanted rotational torque in the event of wind gusts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch control is preferred over rotor brakes, as brakes are subject to failure or overload by the wind force on the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] By contrast, pitch control allows the blades to be feathered, so that wind speed does not affect the stress on the control mechanism.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Pitch control can be implemented via hydraulic or electric mechanisms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Hydraulic mechanisms have longer life, faster response time due to higher driving force, and a lower maintenance backup spring.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] However, hydraulics tend to require more power to keep the system at a high pressure, and can leak.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Electric systems consume and waste less power, and do not leak.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] However, they require costly fail safe batteries and capacitors in the event of power failure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Pitch control does not need to be active (reliant on actuators).
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Passive (stall-controlled) wind turbines rely on the fact that angle of attack increases with wind speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blades can be designed to stop functioning past a certain speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] This is another use for twisted blades: the twist allows for a gradual stall as each portion of the blade has a different angle of attack and will stop at a different time.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Blade pitch control typically accounts for less than 3% of a wind turbine's expense while blade pitch malfunctions account for 23% of all wind turbine production downtime, and account for 21% of all component failures.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] In shipping, blade pitch is measured in the number of inches of forward propulsion through the water for one complete revolution of the propeller.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] For example, a propeller with a 12" pitch will propel the vessel 12" ahead when rotated once.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Note that this is the theoretical maximum distance; in reality, due to "slip" between the propeller and the water, the actual distance propelled will invariably be less.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Some composite propellers have interchangeable blades, which enables the blade pitch to be changed when the propeller is stopped.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] A lower pitch would be used for transporting heavy loads at low speed, whereas a higher pitch would be used for high-speed travel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] In rowing, blade pitch is the inclination of the blade towards the stern of the boat during the drive phase of the rowing stroke.
[src:wind-turbine-control/blade-pitch] Without correct blade pitch, a blade would have a tendency to dive too deep, or pop out of the water and/or cause difficulties with balancing on the recovery phase of the stroke.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A **transmission** (also called a **gearbox**) is a mechanical device invented by Louis Renault (who founded Renault) which uses a gear set—two or more gears working together—to change the speed, direction of rotation, or torque multiplication or reduction, in a machine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] He had been anticipated by Carl Benz, who in 1886 used sprockets and chains to and from an auxiliary shaft and a clutch to provide a second, low gear in the first practical car, his belt-driven Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A transmission can have a single, or *fixed*, gear ratio or it can have *variable* ratios; a *variable-ratio* transmission can have multiple *discrete* gear ratios or be *continuously variable*.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Variable-ratio transmissions are used in many kinds of machinery, especially vehicles.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Early transmissions included the right-angle drives and other gearing in windmills, horse-powered devices, and steam-powered devices.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Applications of these devices included pumps, mills and hoists.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Bicycles conventionally have used hub gear or derailleur gear transmissions, but there are other more recent design innovations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Since the torque and power output of an internal combustion engine (ICE) varies with its (rotational) speed, automobiles powered by ICEs require multiple gear ratios to keep the engine within its power band to produce optimal power, fuel efficiency, and smooth operation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Multiple gear ratios are also needed to provide sufficient acceleration and velocity for safe and reliable operation at modern highway speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] ICEs typically operate over a range of approximately 600–7000 rpm, while the vehicle's speeds requires the wheels to rotate in the range of 0–1800 rpm.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] In the early mass-produced automobiles, the standard transmission design was manual: the combination of gears was selected by the driver through a lever (the gear stick) that displaced gears and gear groups along their axes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Starting in 1939, cars using various types of automatic transmission became available in the US market.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] These vehicles used the engine's own power to change the effective gear ratio depending on the load so as to keep the engine running close to its optimal rotation speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Automatic transmissions now are used in more than two thirds of cars globally, and on almost all new cars in the US.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Most currently produced passenger cars with gasoline or diesel engines use transmissions with 4–10 forward gear ratios (also called *speeds*) and one reverse gear ratio.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Electric vehicles typically use fixed-ratio or two-speed transmissions with no *reverse*, as electric motors can operate efficiently across wider ranges of speed, all the way down to stopped, and change directions electrically.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Electrical vehicles with more than one driven axle often have separate front and rear motors and drive trains rather than longitudinal drive shafts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The simplest transmissions used a fixed ratio to provide either a gear reduction or increase in speed, sometimes in conjunction with a change in the orientation of the output shaft.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Examples of such transmissions are used in helicopters and wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] In the case of a wind turbine, the first stage of the gearbox is usually a planetary gear, to minimize the size while withstanding the high torque inputs from the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Many transmissions – especially for transportation applications – have multiple gears that are used to change the ratio of input speed (e.g. engine speed) to the output speed (e.g. the speed of a car) as required for a given situation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Gear (ratio) selection can be manual, semi-automatic, or automatic.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A manual transmission requires the driver to manually select the gears by operating a gear stick and clutch (which is usually a foot pedal for cars or a hand lever for motorcycles).
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Most transmissions in modern cars use the synchromesh design to synchronise the speeds of the input and output shafts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] However, prior to the 1950s, most cars used non-synchronous transmissions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A sequential manual transmission is a type of non-synchronous transmission used mostly for motorcycles and racing cars.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] It produces faster shift times than synchronized manual transmissions, through the use of dog clutches rather than synchromesh.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Sequential manual transmissions also restrict the driver to selecting either the next or previous gear, in a successive order.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Sequential transmissions can produce more than one distinct whining sound depending on the specific design, but usually the most audible whine changes in pitch with (corresponds to) the speed of the wheels (output shaft), and gets more audible the faster the gears spin.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Nicknamed a "dog box", it is a modern variant of a non-synchronized manual transmission which is constant mesh and used in performance applications, for example, racing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Manual transmissions like this lack the synchronizing part of the synchromesh design and use only the dog clutches specifically made for dog boxes to engage gears.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] For engagement, the selector fork slides a dog clutch with teeth on its side directly onto the side of a constant mesh gear with a similar set of teeth or slots for them, which engages the dog teeth and the gear.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] This design allows for faster and also clutchless shifts, unlike a synchromesh design, but has the advantage of constant mesh, unlike older non-synchronized transmissions used in first automobiles.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Reverse is usually, but not always, in the left-up position.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A semi-automatic transmission is where some of the operation is automated (often the actuation of the clutch), but the driver's input is required to move off from a standstill or to change gears.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] An automated manual transmission (AMT) is essentially a conventional manual transmission that uses automatic actuation to operate the clutch and/or shift between gears.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Many early versions of these transmissions were semi-automatic in operation, such as *Autostick*, which automatically control only the clutch, but still require the driver's input to initiate gear changes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Some of these systems are also referred to as *clutchless manual* systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, can control both the clutch operation and the gear shifts automatically, without any input from the driver.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] An automatic transmission does not require any input from the driver to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions and dual-clutch transmissions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A dual-clutch transmission (DCT) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] In car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] A continuously variable transmission (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous range of gear ratios.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] This contrasts with other transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant speed while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, side-by-sides, motor scooters, snowmobiles, bicycles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain; however, several other designs have also been used at times.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Gearboxes are often a major source of noise and vibration in vehicles and stationary machinery.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Higher sound levels are generally emitted when the vehicle is engaged in lower gears.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The design life of the lower ratio gears is shorter, so cheaper gears may be used, which tend to generate more noise due to smaller overlap ratio and a lower mesh stiffness etc. than the helical gears used for the high ratios.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] This fact has been used to analyze vehicle-generated sound since the late 1960s, and has been incorporated into the simulation of urban roadway noise and corresponding design of urban noise barriers along roadways.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Gears are machine elements aimed to transmit power, their proper design is defined by standard.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] The standard ISO 6336 and AGMA 2001 provide informations regarding the design procedure and define calculation method to verify if gears are safe with respect to different failure mechanism.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Without a correct design and manufacturing of the gears the transmission could present low efficiency, high NVH and low lifetime.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] Gears present several failure mechanism, which are: wear, scuffing, pitting, micro-pitting, tooth flank fracture and tooth root fatigue fracture.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] These mechanisms are due to several phenomena: friction, contact (Hertzian pressure, sliding/rolling), bending fatigue and lack of lubrication.
[src:wind-turbine-control/gearbox] All these phenomena can happen simultaneously and they lead to the failure of the gearbox.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] A variable speed **pitch control** (or **vari-speed**) is a control on an audio device such as a turntable, tape recorder, or CD player that allows the operator to deviate from a standard speed (such as 33, 45 or even 78 rpm on a turntable), resulting in adjustments in pitch.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] The latter term "vari-speed" is more commonly used for tape decks, particularly in the UK.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Analog pitch controls vary the voltage being used by the playback device; digital controls use digital signal processing to change the playback speed or pitch.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] A typical DJ deck allows the pitch to be increased or reduced by up to 8%, which is achieved by increasing or reducing the speed at which the platter rotates.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Turntable or CD playing speed may be changed for beatmatching and other DJ techniques, while pitch shift using a pitch control has myriad uses in sound recording.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Superscope, Inc. of Sun Valley added vari-speed as a feature of portable cassette decks in 1975.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] The C-104 and C-105 models incorporated this feature.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Superscope trademarked the name **Vari-Speed** in 1974.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] The trademark category was **Computer & Software Products & Electrical & Scientific Products.** The trademark goods and Services use was **Magnetic tape recorders and reproducers**.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] By changing pitch, a DJ can alter the speed of an upcoming track to match its tempo to that of the currently playing track so that the beats are synchronized, a technique called beatmatching.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Through beatmatching, a DJ can create smooth transitions between tracks in a DJ set.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Turntables, CDJs, DJ controllers, and DJ software allow DJs to change the speed at which a track is played for this purpose.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Technics SL-1200 turntables allow pitch changes to +/− 8% or 16%, depending on the model, and modern DJ gear often allows a range of +/- 100% (from pausing the track to playing the track twice as fast).
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Modern DJ equipment also features time stretching, which allows the speed of a track to be changed without affecting its pitch, a feature often called "Master Tempo" or "Key Lock".
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] Some equipment also features pitch shifting, allowing pitch to be adjusted independently of tempo; this allows changing the musical key of tracks so that transitions between them sound more pleasing to the listener, a practice called harmonic mixing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/pitch-control] On Technics SL-1200 turntables, pressing the Reset button returns the pitch to a fixed preset value of +/−0% regardless of the pitch control position.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A **wind farm**, also called a **wind park** or **wind power plant**, is a group of wind turbines in the same location used to produce electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms vary in size from a small number of turbines to several hundred wind turbines covering an extensive area.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms may be either onshore or offshore.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Many of the largest operational onshore wind farms are located in China, India, and the United States.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] For example, the largest wind farm in the world, Gansu Wind Farm in China had a capacity of more than 6,000 MW by 2012, with a goal of 20,000 MW by 2020.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of December 2020, the 1218 MW Hornsea Wind Farm in the UK is the largest offshore wind farm in the world.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Individual wind turbine designs continue to increase in power, resulting in fewer turbines being needed for the same total output.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Because they require no fuel, wind farms have less of an effect on the environment than many other forms of power generation and are often referred to as a good source of green energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms have, however, been criticised for their visual and landscape effects.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Typically they need to be spread over more land than other power stations and need to be built in wild and rural areas, which may lead to "industrialization of the countryside", habitat loss, and a drop in tourism.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Some critics claim that wind farms have adverse health effects, but most researchers consider these claims to be pseudoscience (see wind turbine syndrome).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms can interfere with radar, although in most cases, according to the U.S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Department of Energy, "siting and other mitigations have resolved conflicts and allowed wind projects to co-exist effectively with radar".
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Location is critical to the overall success of a wind farm.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Additional conditions contributing to a successful wind farm location include: wind conditions, access to electric transmission, physical access, and local electricity prices.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The faster the average wind speed, the more electricity the wind turbine will generate, so faster winds are generally economically better for wind farm developments.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The balancing factor is that strong gusts and high turbulence require stronger more expensive turbines, otherwise there is a risk of damage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The average power in the wind is not proportional to the average wind speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] For this reason, the ideal wind conditions would be strong but consistent winds with low turbulence coming from a single direction.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Mountain passes are ideal locations for wind farms under these conditions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Mountain passes channel wind, blocked by mountains, through a tunnel-like pass toward areas of lower pressure and flatter land.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Passes used for wind farms such as the San Gorgonio Pass and Altamont Pass are known for their abundant wind resource capacity and capability for large-scale wind farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] These types of passes were the first places in the 1980s to have heavily invested large-scale wind farms after approval for wind energy development by the U.S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] From these wind farms, developers learned much about turbulence and crowding effects of large-scale wind projects, which were previously unresearched, in the U.S. due to the lack of operational wind farms large enough to conduct these types of studies.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Usually sites are screened on the basis of a wind atlas, and validated with on-site wind measurements via long term or permanent meteorological-tower data using anemometers and wind vanes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Meteorological wind data alone is usually not sufficient for accurate siting of a large wind power project.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Collection of site specific data for wind speed and direction is crucial to determining site potential in order to finance the project.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Local winds are often monitored for a year or more, detailed wind maps are constructed, along with rigorous grid capability studies conducted, before any wind generators are installed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The wind blows faster at higher altitudes because of the reduced influence of drag.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The increase in velocity with altitude is most dramatic near the surface and is affected by topography, surface roughness, and upwind obstacles such as trees or buildings.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] At altitudes of thousands of feet/hundreds of metres above sea level, the power in the wind decreases proportional to the decrease in air density.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Often in heavily saturated energy markets, the first step in site selection for large-scale wind projects, before wind resource data collection, is finding areas with adequate available transfer capability (ATC).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] ATC is the measure of the remaining capacity in a transmission system available for further integration of two interconnected areas without significant upgrades to existing transmission lines and substations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Significant equipment upgrades have substantial costs, potentially undermining the viability of a project within a location, regardless of wind resource availability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Once a list of capable areas is constructed, the list is refined based on long term wind measurements, among other environmental or technical limiting factors such as proximity to load and land procurement.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Many independent system operators (ISOs) in the United States such as the California ISO and Midcontinent ISO use interconnection request queues to allow developers to propose a new generation for a specific given area and grid interconnection.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] These request queues have both deposit costs at the time of request and ongoing costs for the studies the ISO will make for up to years after the request was submitted to ascertain the viability of the interconnection due to factors such as ATC.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Larger corporations who can afford to bid the most queues will most likely have market power as to which sites with the most resource and opportunity are eventually developed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] After the deadline to request a place in the queue has passed, many firms will withdraw their requests after gauging the competition in order to make back some of the deposit for each request that is determined too risky in comparison to other larger firms' requests.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A major factor in wind-farm design is the spacing between the turbines, both laterally and axially (with respect to the prevailing winds).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The closer the turbines are together, the more the upwind turbines block wind from their rear neighbors (wake effect).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] However, spacing turbines far apart increases the costs of roads and power cables, and raises the amount of land needed to install a specific capacity of turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As a result of these factors, turbine spacing varies by site.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Generally speaking, manufacturers require a minimum of 3.5 times the turbine's rotor diameter of clear space between each adjacent turbine's respective spatial envelope.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Closer spacing is possible depending on the turbine model, the conditions at the site, and how the site will be operated.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Airflows slow as they approach an obstacle, known as the 'blockage effect', reducing available wind power by 2% for the turbines in front of other turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The capacity of the world's first wind farm was 0.6 MW, produced by 20 wind turbines rated at 30 kilowatts each, installed on the shoulder of Crotched Mountain in southern New Hampshire in December 1980.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Onshore turbine installations in hilly or mountainous regions tend to be on ridges generally three kilometres or more inland from the nearest shoreline.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] This is done to exploit the topographic acceleration as the wind accelerates over a ridge.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The additional wind speeds gained in this way can increase energy produced because more wind goes through the turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The exact position of each turbine matters, because a difference of 30 metres could potentially double output.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] This careful placement is referred to as 'micro-siting'.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Europe is the leader in offshore wind energy, with the first offshore wind farm (Vindeby) being installed in Denmark in 1991.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of 2010, there were 39 offshore wind farms in waters off Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, and the United Kingdom, with a combined operating capacity of 2,396 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] More than 100 GW (or 100,000 MW) of offshore projects are proposed or under development in Europe.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The European Wind Energy Association set a target of 40 GW installed by 2020 and 150 GW by 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of 2017, The Walney Wind Farm in the United Kingdom is the largest offshore wind farm in the world at 659 MW, followed by the London Array (630 MW) also in the UK.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Offshore wind turbines are less obtrusive than turbines on land, as their apparent size and noise is mitigated by distance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Because water has less surface roughness than land (especially deeper water), the average wind speed is usually considerably higher over open water.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Capacity factors (utilisation rates) are considerably higher than for onshore locations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The province of Ontario, Canada is pursuing several proposed locations in the Great Lakes, including the suspended Trillium Power Wind 1 approximately 20 km from shore and over 400 MW in size.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Other Canadian projects include one on the Pacific west coast.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In 2010, there were no offshore wind farms in the United States, but projects were under development in wind-rich areas of the East Coast, Great Lakes, and Pacific coast; and in late 2016 the Block Island Wind Farm was commissioned.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Installation and service / maintenance of off-shore wind farms are a challenge for technology and economic operation of a wind farm.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of 2015, there are 20 jackup vessels for lifting components, but few can lift sizes above 5 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Service vessels have to be operated nearly 24/7 (availability higher than 80% of time) to get sufficient amortisation from the wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Therefore, special fast service vehicles for installation (like Wind Turbine Shuttle) as well as for maintenance (including heave compensation and heave compensated working platforms to allow the service staff to enter the wind turbine also at difficult weather conditions) are required.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] So-called inertial and optical based Ship Stabilization and Motion Control systems (iSSMC) are used for that.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Experimental wind farms consisting of a single wind turbine for testing purposes have been built.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] One such installation is Østerild Wind Turbine Test Field.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Airborne wind farms have been envisaged.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Such wind farms are a group of airborne wind energy systems located close to each other connected to the grid at the same point.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms consisting of diverse wind turbines have been proposed in order to efficiently use wider ranges of wind speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Such wind farms are proposed to be projected under two criteria: maximization of the energy produced by the farm and minimization of its costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Australian Greens have been significant supporters of Australian wind farms, however the party's previous leader Bob Brown and former leader Richard Di Natale have now both expressed concerns about environmental aspects of wind turbines, particularly the potential danger they impose for birds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In July 2022 Brazil reached 22 GW of installed wind power in about 750 wind farms In 2021 Brazil was the seventh country in the world in terms of installed wind power (21 GW), and the 4th largest producer of wind energy in the world (72 TWh), behind China, USA and Germany.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The largest wind farm in the country is the Complexo eólico Lagoa dos Ventos in the State of Piauí, onshore with a current capacity of 1,000 MW being expanded to 1,500 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In just five years, China leapfrogged the rest of the world in wind energy production, going from 2,599 MW of capacity in 2006 to 62,733 MW at the end of 2011.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] However, the rapid growth outpaced China's infrastructure and new construction slowed significantly in 2012.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] At the end of 2009, wind power in China accounted for 25.1 gigawatts (GW) of electricity generating capacity, and China has identified wind power as a key growth component of the country's economy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] With its large land mass and long coastline, China has exceptional wind resources.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Researchers from Harvard and Tsinghua University have found that China could meet all of their electricity demands from wind power by 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] By the end of 2008, at least 15 Chinese companies were commercially producing wind turbines and several dozen more were producing components.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Turbine sizes of 1.5 MW to 3 MW became common.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Leading wind power companies in China were Goldwind, Dongfang Electric, and Sinovel along with most major foreign wind turbine manufacturers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] China also increased production of small-scale wind turbines to about 80,000 turbines (80 MW) in 2008.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Through all these developments, the Chinese wind industry appeared unaffected by the 2008 financial crisis, according to industry observers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] According to the Global Wind Energy Council, the development of wind energy in China, in terms of scale and rhythm, is unparalleled in the world.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The National People's Congress permanent committee passed a law that requires the Chinese energy companies to purchase all the electricity produced by the renewable energy sector.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In 2011 the European Union had a total installed wind capacity of 93,957 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Germany had the third-largest capacity in the world (after China and the United States), with an installed capacity of 29,060 MW at the end of 2011.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Spain had 21,674 MW, and Italy and France each had between 6,000 and 7,000 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] By January 2014, the UK installed capacity was 10,495 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] But energy production can be different from capacity – in 2010, Spain had the highest European wind power production with 43 TWh compared to Germany's 35 TWh.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] An important limiting factor of wind power is variable power generated by wind farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In most locations the wind blows only part of the time, which means that there has to be back-up capacity of dispatchable generation capacity to cover periods that the wind is not blowing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The idea is that by the time a low pressure area has moved away from Denmark to the Baltic Sea the next low appears off the coast of Ireland.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Therefore, while it is true that the wind is not blowing everywhere all of the time, it will tend to be blowing somewhere.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In July 2022, Seagreen, the world's deepest fixed-bottom wind farm, became operative.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Located 26 miles off the Angus coastline, in Scotland, it has 114 turbines that generate 1.1 gigawatts (GW) of electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] India has the fifth largest installed wind power capacity in the world.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of March 2025, the installed capacity of wind power was 50037.82 MW mainly spread across Tamil Nadu state (11739.91 MW) and Gujarat state (12677.48 MW).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind power accounts nearly 8.5% of India's total installed power generation capacity, and it generates 1.6% of the country's power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In Japan's electricity sector, wind power generates a small proportion of the country's electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] It has been estimated that Japan has the potential for 144 gigawatts (GW) for onshore wind and 608 GW of offshore wind capacity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of 2023, the country had a total installed capacity of 5.2 GW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of 2018, government targets for wind power deployment were relatively low when compared to other countries, at 1.7% of electricity production by 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In December 2020, the Japanese government announced plans to install up to 45 GW of offshore wind power by 2040.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The 117 MW Tafila Wind Farm in Jordan was inaugurated in December 2015, and is the first large scale wind farm project in the region.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Morocco has undertaken a vast wind energy program, to support the development of renewable energy and energy efficiency in the country.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Moroccan Integrated Wind Energy Project, spanning over a period of 10 years with a total investment estimated at $3.25 billion, will enable the country to bring the installed capacity, from wind energy, from 280 MW in 2010 to 2000 MW in 2020.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Pakistan has wind corridors in Jhimpir, Gharo and Keti Bundar in Sindh province and is currently developing wind power plants in Jhimpir and Mirpur Sakro (District Thatta).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The government of Pakistan decided to develop wind power energy sources due to problems supplying energy to the southern coastal regions of Sindh and Balochistan.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Zorlu Energy Putin Power Plant is the first wind power plant in Pakistan.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The wind farm is being developed in Jhimpir, by Zorlu Energy Pakistan the local subsidiary of a Turkish company.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The total cost of the project is $136 million.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Completed in 2012, it has a total capacity of approximately 56MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Fauji Fertilizer Company Energy Limited, has built a 49.5 MW wind Energy Farm at Jhimpir.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Contract of supply of mechanical design was awarded to Nordex and Descon Engineering Limited.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Nordex is a German wind turbine manufacturer.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In the end of 2011 49.6 MW was expected to be completed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Pakistani government also issued a Letter Of Interest in a 100 MW Wind power plant to FFCEL.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Pakistani government had plans to achieve electric power generation of up to 2500 MW by the end of 2015 from wind energy to bring down an energy shortage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In the Gharo wind corridor, two wind farms (Foundation Energy 1 & II each 49.5 MW) are operational while two wind farms Tenaga Generasi Limited 49.5 MW and HydroChina Dawood Power Pvt.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Limited 49.5 are under construction and expected to achieve COD in 2017.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] According to a USAID report, Pakistan has the potential of producing 150,000 megawatts of wind energy, of which the Sindh corridor can produce 40,000 megawatts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Philippines has the first windfarm in Southeast Asia.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Located in the northern part of the country's biggest island, Luzon, alongside the seashore of Bangui, Ilocos Norte.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The wind farm uses 20 units of 70-metre (230 ft) high Vestas V82 1.65 MW wind turbines, arranged on a single row stretching along a nine-kilometre shoreline off Bangui Bay, facing the South China Sea.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Phase I of the NorthWind power project in Bangui Bay consists of 15 wind turbines, each capable of producing electricity up to a maximum capacity of 1.65 MW, for a total of 24.75 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The 15 on-shore turbines are spaced 326 metres (1,070 ft) apart, each 70 metres (230 ft) high, with 41 metres (135 ft) long blades, with a rotor diameter of 82 metres (269 ft) and a wind swept area of 5,281 square metres (56,840 sq ft).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Phase II was completed in August 2008, and added 5 more wind turbines with the same capacity, and brought the total capacity to 33 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] All 20 turbines describes a graceful arc reflecting the shoreline of Bangui Bay.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Adjacent municipalities of Burgos and Pagudpud followed with 50 and 27 wind turbines with a capacity of 3 MW each for a Total of 150 MW and 81 MW respectively.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Two other wind farms were built outside of Ilocos Norte, the Pililla Wind Farm in Rizal and the Mindoro Wind Farm near Puerto Galera in Oriental Mindoro.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Sri Lanka has received funding from the Asian Development Bank amounting to $300 million to invest in renewable energies.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] From this funding as well as $80 million from the Sri Lankan Government and $60 million from France's Agence Française de Développement, Sri Lanka was expected to build two 100MW wind farms from 2017 due to be completed by late 2020 in northern Sri Lanka.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As of September 2015, a number of sizable wind farms have been constructed in South Africa mostly in the Western Cape region.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] These include the 100 MW Sere Wind Farm and the 138 MW Gouda Wind Facility.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Most future wind farms in South Africa are earmarked for locations along the Eastern Cape coastline.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Eskom has constructed one small scale prototype windfarm at Klipheuwel in the Western Cape and another demonstrator site is near Darling with phase 1 completed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The first commercial wind farm, Coega Wind Farm in Port Elisabeth, was developed by the Belgian company Electrawinds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] U.S. wind power installed capacity in September 2019 exceeded 100,125 MW and supplies 6.94% of the nation's electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The majority of wind farms in the United States are located in the Central Plains, with slow expansion into other regions of the country.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Growth in 2008 channeled some $17 billion into the economy, positioning wind power as one of the leading sources of new power generation in the country, along with natural gas.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind projects completed in 2008 accounted for about 42% of the entire new power-producing capacity added in the U.S. during the year.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Texas, with 27,036 MW of capacity, has the most installed wind power capacity of any U.S. state, followed by Iowa with 8,965 MW and Oklahoma with 8,072 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Iowa is the leading state in terms of wind energy accounting for nearly 40% of total energy production in 2019.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The Alta Wind Energy Center (1,020 MW) in California is the nation's largest wind farm in terms of capacity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Altamont Pass Wind Farm is the largest wind farm in the U.S. in terms of the number of individual turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] At the end of 2019, about 114,000 people were employed in the U.S. wind industry, and GE Energy was the largest domestic wind turbine manufacturer.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In 2018, U.S. wind power provided enough electricity to power approximately 25 million homes, avoiding the emissions of 200 million tons of carbon.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In the USSR, plans to use wind energy were made in the early 1920s (the use of wind energy for irrigation systems in the Baku region was mentioned in a letter from V.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The first wind power station in the USSR was built in 1931 in Balaklava.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] After the Axis invasion against the USSR it was destroyed during the occupation of the Crimean Peninsula by Axis invaders.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In 1951, the Ural Electromechanical Plant began mass production of standard wind power stations for collective farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In the period 1945-1970, more than 40 thousand wind turbines were made in the USSR, most of them were installed in rural areas on state farms and collective farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In the early 1980s, a plan was developed in the USSR to build wind power plants to provide energy to autonomous facilities in the Far North (the construction of which was to be carried out by military builders).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Later, an experimental farm with several wind turbines was built on the bank of the river Desna in the Vyshgorod district of the Kiev region.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The environmental impact of electricity generation from wind power is minor when compared to that of fossil fuel power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind power consumes no fuel, and emits no air pollution, unlike fossil fuels.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind turbines have some of the lowest global warming potential per unit of electricity generated: far less greenhouse gas is emitted than for the average unit of electricity, so wind power helps limit climate change.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Emissions from production of a turbine are recouped in less than a year of operation, as it replaces gas or coal power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Onshore (on-land) wind farms can have a significant visual impact and impact on the landscape.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Due to a very low surface power density and spacing requirements, wind farms typically need to be spread over more land than other power stations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Conflicts arise especially in scenic and culturally-important landscapes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Siting restrictions, such as setbacks, may be implemented to limit the impact.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The land between the turbines and access roads can still be used for farming and grazing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Some wind farms are opposed for potentially spoiling protected scenic areas, archaeological landscapes and heritage sites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Many wind turbine blades are made of fiberglass and some only had a lifetime of 10 to 20 years.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Previously, there was no market for recycling these old blades, and they were commonly disposed of in landfills.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Because blades are hollow, they take up a large volume compared to their mass.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Since 2019, some landfill operators have begun requiring blades to be crushed before being landfilled.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Blade end-of-life is complicated, and blades manufactured in the 2020s are more likely to be designed to be completely recyclable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] At a distance of 300 metres (980 ft) this may be around 45 dB, which is slightly louder than a refrigerator.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] At 1.5 km (1 mi) distance they become inaudible.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Some people who live very close to wind turbines have reported negative health effects, but peer-reviewed research has generally not supported these claims.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Pile-driving to construct non-floating wind farms is noisy underwater, but in operation offshore wind is much quieter than ships.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] but the worldwide ecological impact is minimal.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] though wind turbines are responsible for far fewer bird deaths than fossil-fueled power stations when climate change effects are included.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The effects of wind turbines on birds can be mitigated with proper wildlife monitoring.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In a 2009 report about "Rural Wind Farms", a Standing Committee of the Parliament of New South Wales, Australia, recommended a minimum setback of two kilometres between wind turbines and neighboring houses (which may be waived by the affected neighbor) as a precautionary approach.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A 2014 paper suggests that the 'Wind Turbine Syndrome' is mainly caused by the nocebo effect and other psychological mechanisms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Utility-scale wind farms must have access to transmission lines to transport energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The wind farm developer may be obliged to install extra equipment or control systems in the wind farm to meet the technical standards set by the operator of a transmission line.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The intermittent nature of wind power may pose complications for maintaining a stable power grid when wind farms provide a large percentage of electricity in any one region.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] However wind farms are more resistant to military attack than thermal power plants as many missiles are needed to destroy them not just one.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] In 2021, Assistant Professor at MIT, Priya Donti was awarded the U.S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Donti is working on another project not yet released that has been noted to work 10 times faster than current technology and at a fraction of the price.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind farms may interfere with ground radar systems used for military, weather, and air traffic control.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The large, rapidly moving blades of the turbines can return signals to the radar that can be mistaken as an aircraft or weather pattern.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Actual aircraft and weather patterns around wind farms can be accurately detected, as there is no fundamental physical constraint preventing that, but aging radar infrastructure is significantly challenged with the task.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The US military is using wind turbines on some bases, including Barstow near the radar test facility.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The level of interference is a function of the signal processors used within the radar, the speed of the aircraft and the relative orientation of wind turbines/aircraft with respect to the radar.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] An aircraft flying above the wind farm's turning blades could become impossible to detect because the blade tips can be moving at nearly aircraft velocity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Studies are currently being performed to determine the level of this interference and will be used in future site planning.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Issues include masking (shadowing), clutter (noise), and signal alteration.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Radar issues have stalled as much as 10,000 MW of projects in the USA.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Some very long range radars are not affected by wind farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Permanent problem solving include a *non-initiation window* to hide the turbines while still tracking aircraft over the wind farm, and a similar method mitigates the false returns.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] England's Newcastle Airport is using a short-term mitigation; to "blank" the turbines on the radar map with a software patch.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Wind turbine blades using stealth technology are being developed to mitigate radar reflection problems for aviation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] As well as stealth windfarms, the future development of infill radar systems could filter out the turbine interference.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A mobile radar system, the Lockheed Martin TPS-77, can distinguish between aircraft and wind turbines, and more than 170 TPS-77 radars are in use around the world.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] The United States Federal Aviation Administration advises aircraft without position-reporting technologies such as transponders to avoid flight within 1 nautical mile (1.9 km; 1.2 mi) at all altitudes from wind turbine farms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] There are reports of negative effects on radio and television reception in wind farm communities.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Potential solutions include predictive interference modelling as a component of site selection.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A 2010 study found that in the immediate vicinity of wind farms, the climate is cooler during the day and slightly warmer during the night than the surrounding areas due to the turbulence generated by the blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] Even at the height of summer heat, the lowering of 2.5–3 degrees above the crops due to turbulence caused by the blades can make a difference for the cultivation of corn.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-farm] A December 2025 study conducted by Dalian Ocean University in China and Murdoch University in Australia indicates that marine life thrived and appears to have had a significant increase in benefits associated with an offshore wind farm in the northern Yellow Sea in China.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In 1919, German physicist Albert Betz showed that for a hypothetical ideal wind-energy extraction machine, the fundamental laws of conservation of mass and energy allowed no more than 16/27 (59.3%) of the wind's kinetic energy to be captured.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This Betz's law limit can be approached by modern turbine designs which reach 70 to 80% of this theoretical limit.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In addition to the blades, design of a complete wind power system must also address the hub, controls, generator, supporting structure and foundation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Turbines must also be integrated into power grids.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Blade shape and dimension are determined by the aerodynamic performance required to efficiently extract energy, and by the strength required to resist forces on the blade.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The aerodynamics of a horizontal-axis wind turbine are not straightforward.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The air flow at the blades is not the same as that away from the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The way that energy is extracted from the air also causes air to be deflected by the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind turbine aerodynamics at the rotor surface exhibit phenomena that are rarely seen in other aerodynamic fields.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Rotation speed must be controlled for efficient power generation and to keep the turbine components within speed and torque limits.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The centrifugal force on the blades increases as the square of the rotation speed, which makes this structure sensitive to overspeed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Because power increases as the cube of the wind speed, turbines must survive much higher wind loads (such as gusts of wind) than those loads from which they generate power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A wind turbine must produce power over a range of wind speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The cut-in speed is around 3–4 m/s for most turbines, and cut-out at 25 m/s.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] If the rated wind speed is exceeded the power has to be limited.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A control system involves three basic elements: sensors to measure process variables, actuators to manipulate energy capture and component loading, and control algorithms that apply information gathered by the sensors to coordinate the actuators.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Any wind blowing above the survival speed damages the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The survival speed of commercial wind turbines ranges from 40 m/s (144 km/h, 89 MPH) to 72 m/s (259 km/h, 161 MPH), typically around 60 m/s (216 km/h, 134 MPH).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Some turbines can survive 80 metres per second (290 km/h; 180 mph).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A stall on an airfoil occurs when air passes over it in such a way that the generation of lift rapidly decreases.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Usually this is due to a high angle of attack (AOA), but can also result from dynamic effects.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The blades of a fixed pitch turbine can be designed to stall in high wind speeds, slowing rotation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This is a simple fail-safe mechanism to help prevent damage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, other than systems with dynamically controlled pitch, it cannot produce a constant power output over a large range of wind speeds, which makes it less suitable for large scale, power grid applications.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A fixed-speed HAWT (Horizontal Axis Wind Turbine) inherently increases its angle of attack at higher wind speed as the blades speed up.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A natural strategy, then, is to allow the blade to stall when the wind speed increases.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This technique was successfully used on many early HAWTs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, the degree of blade pitch tended to increase noise levels.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Vortex generators may be used to control blade lift characteristics.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] VGs are placed on the airfoil to enhance the lift if they are placed on the lower (flatter) surface or limit the maximum lift if placed on the upper (higher camber) surface.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Furling works by decreasing the angle of attack, which reduces drag and blade cross-section.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] One major problem is getting the blades to stall or furl quickly enough in a wind gust.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A fully furled turbine blade, when stopped, faces the edge of the blade into the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Loads can be reduced by making a structural system softer or more flexible.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This can be accomplished with downwind rotors or with curved blades that twist naturally to reduce angle of attack at higher wind speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] These systems are nonlinear and couple the structure to the flow field - requiring design tools to evolve to model these nonlinearities.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Standard turbines all furl in high winds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Since furling requires acting against the torque on the blade, it requires some form of pitch angle control, which is achieved with a slewing drive.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This drive precisely angles the blade while withstanding high torque loads.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In addition, many turbines use hydraulic systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] These systems are usually spring-loaded, so that if hydraulic power fails, the blades automatically furl.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Other turbines use an electric servomotor for every blade.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] They have a battery-reserve in case of grid failure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Small wind turbines (under 50 kW) with variable-pitching generally use systems operated by centrifugal force, either by flyweights or geometric design, and avoid electric or hydraulic controls.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Fundamental gaps exist in pitch control, limiting the reduction of energy costs, according to a report funded by the Atkinson Center for a Sustainable Future.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Load reduction is currently focused on full-span blade pitch control, since individual pitch motors are the actuators on commercial turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Significant load mitigation has been demonstrated in simulations for blades, tower, and drive train.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, further research is needed to increase energy capture and mitigate fatigue loads.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A control technique applied to the pitch angle is done by comparing the power output with the power value at the rated engine speed (power reference, Ps reference).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Pitch control is done with PI controller.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In order to adjust pitch rapidly enough, the actuator uses the time constant Tservo, an integrator and limiters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The pitch angle remains from 0° to 30° with a change rate of 10°/second.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As in the figure at the right, the reference pitch angle is compared with the actual pitch angle b and then the difference is corrected by the actuator.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The reference pitch angle, which comes from the PI controller, goes through a limiter.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Restrictions are important to maintain the pitch angle in real terms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Limiting the change rate is especially important during network faults.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The importance is due to the fact that the controller decides how quickly it can reduce the aerodynamic energy to avoid acceleration during errors.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Modern large wind turbines operate at variable speeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] When wind speed falls below the turbine's rated speed, generator torque is used to control the rotor speed to capture as much power as possible.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The most power is captured when the tip speed ratio is held constant at its optimum value (typically between 6 and 7).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This means that rotor speed increases proportional to wind speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The difference between the aerodynamic torque captured by the blades and the applied generator torque controls the rotor speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] If the generator torque is lower, the rotor accelerates, and if the generator torque is higher, the rotor slows.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Below rated wind speed, the generator torque control is active while the blade pitch is typically held at the constant angle that captures the most power, fairly flat to the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Above rated wind speed, the generator torque is typically held constant while the blade pitch is adjusted accordingly.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] One technique to control a permanent magnet synchronous motor is field-oriented control.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Field-oriented control is a closed loop strategy composed of two current controllers (an inner loop and cascading outer loop) necessary for controlling the torque, and one speed controller.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In this control strategy the d axis current is kept at zero, while the vector current aligns with the q axis in order to maintain the torque angle at 90o.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This is a common control strategy because only the Iqs current must be controlled.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The torque equation of the generator is a linear equation dependent only on the Iqs current.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Thus, the complete system of the machine side converter and the cascaded PI controller loops is given by the figure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The control inputs are the duty rations mds and mqs, of the PWM-regulated converter.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] It displays the control scheme for the wind turbine in the machine side and simultaneously how the Ids to zero (the torque equation is linear).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Large turbines are typically actively controlled to face the wind direction measured by a wind vane situated on the back of the nacelle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] By minimizing the yaw angle (the misalignment between wind and turbine pointing direction), power output is maximized and non-symmetrical loads minimized.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, since wind direction varies, the turbine does not strictly follow the wind and experiences a small yaw angle on average.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The power output losses can be approximated to fall with (cos(yaw angle))3.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Particularly at low-to-medium wind speeds, yawing can significantly reduce output, with wind common variations reaching 30°.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] At high wind speeds, wind direction is less variable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Braking a small turbine can be done by dumping energy from the generator into a resistor bank, converting kinetic energy into heat.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This method is useful if the kinetic load on the generator is suddenly reduced or is too small to keep the turbine speed within its allowed limit.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Cyclically braking slows the blades, which increases the stalling effect and reducing efficiency.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Rotation can be kept at a safe speed in faster winds while maintaining (nominal) power output.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This method is usually not applied on large, grid-connected wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A mechanical drum brake or disc brake stops rotation in emergency situations such as extreme gust events.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The brake is a secondary means to hold the turbine at rest for maintenance, with a rotor lock system as primary means.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Such brakes are usually applied only after blade furling and electromagnetic braking have reduced the turbine speed because mechanical brakes can ignite a fire inside the nacelle if used at full speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Turbine load increases if the brake is applied at rated RPM.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The smallest, with power less than 10 kW are used in homes, farms and remote applications whereas intermediate wind turbines (10-250 kW ) are useful for village power, hybrid systems and distributed power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The world's largest wind turbine as of 2021 was Vestas' V236-15.0 MW turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The new design's blades offer the largest swept area in the world with three 115.5 metres (379 ft) blades giving a rotor diameter of 236 metres (774 ft).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Ming Yang in China have announced a larger 16 MW design.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] For a given wind speed, turbine mass is approximately proportional to the cube of its blade-length.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind power intercepted is proportional to the square of blade-length.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The maximum blade-length of a turbine is limited by strength, stiffness, and transport considerations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Labor and maintenance costs increase slower than turbine size, so to minimize costs, wind farm turbines are basically limited by the strength of materials, and siting requirements.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Utility-scale wind turbine generators have minimum temperature operating limits that apply in areas with temperatures below −20 °C (−4 °F).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Turbines must be protected from ice accumulation that can make anemometer readings inaccurate and which, in certain turbine control designs, can cause high structure loads and damage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Some turbine manufacturers offer low-temperature packages at extra cost, which include internal heaters, different lubricants, and different alloys for structural elements.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] If low-temperatures are combined with a low-wind condition, the turbine requires an external supply of power, equivalent to a few percent of its rated output, for internal heating.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Leon Wind Farm in Manitoba, Canada, has a total rating of 99 MW and is estimated to need up to 3 MW (around 3% of capacity) of station service power a few days a year for temperatures down to −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The nacelle houses the gearbox and generator connecting the tower and rotor.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Sensors detect the wind speed and direction, and motors turn the nacelle into the wind to maximize output.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In conventional wind turbines, the blades spin a shaft that is connected through a gearbox to the generator.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The gearbox converts the turning speed of the blades (15 to 20 RPM for a one-megawatt turbine) into the 1,800 (750-3600) RPM that the generator needs to generate electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Gearboxes are one of the more expensive components for installing and maintaining wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Analysts from GlobalData estimate that the gearbox market grew from $3.2bn in 2006 to $6.9bn in 2011.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The market leader for Gearbox production was Winergy in 2011.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The use of magnetic gearboxes has been explored as a way of reducing maintenance costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] For large horizontal-axis wind turbines (HAWT), the generator is mounted in a nacelle at the top of a tower, behind the rotor hub.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Older wind turbines generate electricity through asynchronous machines directly connected to the grid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The gearbox reduces generator cost and weight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Commercial generators have a rotor carrying a winding so that a rotating magnetic field is produced inside a set of windings called the stator.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] While the rotating winding consumes a fraction of a percent of the generator output, adjustment of the field current allows good control over the output voltage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The rotor's varying output frequency and voltage can be matched to the fixed values of the grid using multiple technologies such as doubly fed induction generators or full-effect converters, which converts the variable frequency current to DC and then back to AC using inverters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Although such alternatives require costly equipment and cost power, the turbine can capture a significantly larger fraction of the wind energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Most are low voltage 660 Volt, but some offshore turbines (several MW) are 3.3 kV medium voltage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In some cases, especially when offshore, a large collector transformer converts the wind farm's medium-voltage AC grid to DC and transmits the energy through a power cable to an onshore HVDC converter station.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Hydraulic wind turbines perform the frequency and torque adjustments of gearboxes via a pressurized hydraulic fluid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Typically, the action of the turbine pressurizes the fluid with a hydraulic pump at the nacelle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Meanwhile, components on the ground can transform this pressure into energy, and recirculate the working fluid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Typically, the working fluid used in this kind of hydrostatic transmission is oil, which serves as a lubricant, reducing losses due to friction in the hydraulic units and allowing for a broad range of operating temperatures.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, other concepts are currently under study, which involve using water as the working fluid because it is abundant and eco-friendly.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Hydraulic turbines provide benefits to both operation and capital costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] They can use hydraulic units with variable displacement to have a continuously variable transmission that adapts in real time.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This decouples generator speed to rotor speed, avoiding stalling and allowing for operating the turbine at an optimum speed and torque.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This built-in transmission is how these hydraulic systems avoid the need for a conventional gearbox.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Furthermore, hydraulic instead of mechanical power conversion introduces a damping effect on rotation fluctuations, reducing fatigue of the drivetrain and improving turbine structural integrity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Additionally, using a pressurized fluid instead of mechanical components allows for the electrical conversion to occur on the ground instead of the nacelle: this reduces maintenance difficulty, and reduces weight and center of gravity of the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Studies estimate that these benefits may yield to a 3.9-18.9% reduction in the levelized cost of power for offshore wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Some years ago, Mitsubishi, through its branch Artemis, deployed the Sea Angel, a unique hydraulic wind turbine at the utility scale.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The Digital Displacement technology underwent trials on the Sea Angel, a wind turbine rated at 7 MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This design is capable of adjusting the displacement of the central unit in response to erratic wind velocities, thereby maintaining the optimal efficiency of the system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Still, these systems are newer and in earlier stages of commercialization compared to conventional gearboxes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Gearless wind turbines (also called direct drive) eliminate the gearbox.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Instead, the rotor shaft is attached directly to the generator, which spins at the same speed as the blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Advantages of permanent magnet direct drive generators (PMDD) over geared generators include increased efficiency, reduced noise, longer lifetime, high torque at low RPM, faster and precise positioning, and drive stiffness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] PMDD generators "eliminate the gear-speed increaser, which is susceptible to significant accumulated fatigue torque loading, related reliability issues, and maintenance costs".
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] To make up for a direct-drive generator's slower rotation rate, the diameter of the generator's rotor is increased so that it can contain more magnets to create the required frequency and power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Gearless wind turbines are often heavier than geared wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] An EU study showed that gearbox reliability is not the main problem in wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The reliability of direct drive turbines offshore is still not known, given the small sample size.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Experts from Technical University of Denmark estimate that a geared generator with permanent magnets may require 25 kg/MW of the rare-earth element neodymium, while a gearless may use 250 kg/MW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In December 2011, the US Department of Energy announced a critical shortage of rare-earth elements such as neodymium.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] China produces more than 95% of rare-earth elements, while Hitachi holds more than 600 patents covering neodymium magnets.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Direct-drive turbines require 600 kg of permanent magnet material per megawatt, which translates to several hundred kilograms of rare-earth content per megawatt, as neodymium content is estimated to be 31% of magnet weight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Hybrid drivetrains (intermediate between direct drive and traditional geared) use significantly less rare-earth materials.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] While permanent magnet wind turbines only account for about 5% of the market outside of China, their market share inside of China is estimated at 25% or higher.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In 2011, demand for neodymium in wind turbines was estimated to be 1/5 of that in electric vehicles.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The ratio between the blade speed and the wind speed is called tip-speed ratio.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] High efficiency 3-blade-turbines have tip speed/wind speed ratios of 6 to 7.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind turbines spin at varying speeds (a consequence of their generator design).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Use of aluminum and composite materials has contributed to low rotational inertia, which means that newer wind turbines can accelerate quickly if the winds pick up, keeping the tip speed ratio more nearly constant.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Operating closer to their optimal tip speed ratio during energetic gusts of wind allows wind turbines to improve energy capture from sudden gusts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] To increase tip speed without increasing noise would reduce torque into the gearbox and generator, reducing structural loads, thereby reducing cost.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The noise reduction is linked to the detailed blade aerodynamics, especially factors that reduce abrupt stalling.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The inability to predict stall restricts the use of aggressive aerodynamics.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Some blades have a winglet to increase performance and reduce noise.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A blade can have a lift-to-drag ratio of 120, compared to 70 for a sailplane and 15 for an airliner.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In order to optimize the lift-to-drag ratio of a blade, they are typically designed with varying airfoil cross-sections along their length, customized to the varying wind speeds and angles encountered from root to tip.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] An additional design improvement is the incorporation of vortex generators, small fins mounted to the surface of the blade, the help to smooth the airflow, preventing flow separation and reducing turbulence, both of which contribute to reducing energy losses.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] All of these innovations have the end goal of increasing the efficiency of converting wind energy to electricity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Study of the hydrodynamics of the knobbly flippers of the humpback whale by the marine biologist Frank E.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Fish led to an improved design of wind turbine blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The role of the Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) in wind power generation is to measure the three-axis acceleration and angular velocity of wind turbine blades, hubs, and tower tops in real-time.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] By using inertial navigation algorithms, it calculates the motion states (position, velocity, and attitude) of these components.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] IMU captures the global dynamic information of wind turbines and, through data fusion with Kalman filters and GNSS data, reduces cumulative errors.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This enables high-precision estimation of blade deflection and loads, providing critical support for monitoring the operational loads of wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] IMUs measure angular velocity and acceleration, which, combined with navigation algorithms, capture the flexural attitude and positional changes of blades during operation in real time.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Through the use of Kalman filters (KF) to fuse data from multiple IMUs, and based on rigid body geometric models and rotor angles, the position of each IMU is determined.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Precision is further enhanced by compensating for differences between actual positions and the model.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] *Absolute Position Reference*: By integrating IMU data, it limits drift errors, ensuring convergence and accuracy in IMU navigation solutions (position and attitude).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] IMU can be combined with other sensors (e.g., vibration and stress sensors) to improve fault detection sensitivity through multi-source data fusion.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] For example, IMUs installed on the turbine main shaft can extract tower acceleration signals through signal processing and use azimuth information to identify specific faults.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Multi-sensor fusion technology can detect blade stress changes and crack risks, reducing downtime losses.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In 2021, Chinese researchers proposed an innovative multi-IMU data fusion algorithm for wind turbine blade dynamic deformation sensing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This algorithm uses a relative motion sensing fusion method that employs an improved Kalman filter and a feedback-based distributed structure to achieve multi-node data fusion.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Low-precision IMUs (sub-nodes) are distributed at different positions along the blade, sensing local dynamic deformations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Data from the high-precision IMU is filtered and fused to correct the measurement errors of low-precision IMUs, significantly improving the system's overall measurement accuracy and fault tolerance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Each sub-node independently processes local data, and redundant information is integrated through a global fusion layer to enhance fault tolerance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Even if a single IMU fails, the system can maintain high accuracy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] During wind turbine blade dynamic testing, blades undergo continuous motion under external forces.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] By combining global reference data from high-precision IMUs with local measurements from low-precision IMUs, multi-node data fusion is achieved through a federated Kalman filter.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This enables precise perception of the blade's flexural attitude and position in three-dimensional space.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Simulation results show that the fusion algorithm effectively reduces the measurement errors of low-precision IMUs, significantly decreasing the relative position and attitude errors of local blade nodes while maintaining the accuracy of high-precision IMU nodes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Particularly for complex motions at the blade's middle and tip, the fusion algorithm demonstrates strong robustness and accuracy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In simple designs, the blades are directly bolted to the hub and are unable to pitch, which leads to aerodynamic stall above certain windspeeds.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In more sophisticated designs, they are bolted to the pitch bearing, which adjusts their angle of attack with the help of a pitch system according to the wind speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Pitch control is performed by hydraulic or electric systems (battery or ultracapacitor).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The hub is fixed to the rotor shaft, which drives the generator directly or through a gearbox.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The number of blades is selected for aerodynamic efficiency, component costs, and system reliability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Noise emissions are affected by the location of the blades upwind or downwind of the tower and the rotor speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Given that the noise emissions from the blades' trailing edges and tips vary by the 5th power of blade speed, a small increase in tip speed dramatically increases noise.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind turbines almost universally use either two or three blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, patents present designs with additional blades, such as Chan Shin's multi-unit rotor blade system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Aerodynamic efficiency increases with number of blades but with diminishing return.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Increasing from one to two yields a six percent increase, while going from two to three yields an additional three percent.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Further increasing the blade count yields minimal improvements and sacrifices too much in blade stiffness as the blades become thinner.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Theoretically, an infinite number of blades of zero width is the most efficient, operating at a high value of the tip speed ratio, but this is not practical.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Component costs affected by blade count are primarily for materials and manufacturing of the turbine rotor and drive train.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Generally, the lower the number of blades, the lower the material and manufacturing costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In addition, fewer blades allow higher rotational speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Blade stiffness requirements to avoid tower interference limit blade thickness, but only when the blades are upwind of the tower; deflection in a downwind machine increases tower clearance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Fewer blades with higher rotational speeds reduce peak torque in the drive train, resulting in lower gearbox and generator costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] System reliability is affected by blade count primarily through the dynamic loading of the rotor into the drive train and tower systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] While aligning the wind turbine to changes in wind direction (yawing), each blade experiences a cyclic load at its root end depending on blade position.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, these cyclic loads when combined at the drive train shaft are symmetrically balanced for three blades, yielding smoother operation during yaw.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] One or two blade turbines can use a pivoting teetered hub to nearly eliminate the cyclic loads into the drive shaft and system during yawing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In 2012, a Chinese 3.6 MW two-blade turbine was tested in Denmark.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Increasing blade length pushed power generation from the single megawatt range to upwards of 10 megawatts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A larger area effectively increases tip-speed ratio at a given wind speed, thus increasing its energy extraction.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Software such as HyperSizer (originally developed for spacecraft design) can be used to improve blade design.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As of 2015 the rotor diameters of onshore wind turbine blades reached 130 meters, while the diameter of offshore turbines reached 170 meters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In 2001, an estimated 50 million kilograms of fiberglass laminate were used in wind turbine blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] An important goal is to control blade weight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Since blade mass scales as the cube of the turbine radius, gravity loading constrains systems with larger blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Gravitational loads include axial and tensile/ compressive loads (top/bottom of rotation) as well as bending (lateral positions).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The magnitude of these loads fluctuates cyclically and the edgewise moments (see below) are reversed every 180° of rotation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Typical rotor speeds and design life are ~10 and 20 years, respectively, with the number of lifetime revolutions on the order of 10^8.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Considering wind, it is expected that turbine blades go through ~10^9 loading cycles.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind is another source of rotor blade loading.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Lift causes bending in the flatwise direction (out of rotor plane) while airflow around the blade cause edgewise bending (in the rotor plane).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Flaps bending involves tension on the pressure (upwind) side and compression on the suction (downwind) side.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Edgewise bending involves tension on the leading edge and compression on the trailing edge.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind loads are cyclical because of natural variability in wind speed and wind shear (higher speeds at top of rotation).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Failure in ultimate loading of wind-turbine rotor blades exposed to wind and gravity loading is a failure mode that needs to be considered when the rotor blades are designed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The wind speed that causes bending of the rotor blades exhibits a natural variability, and so does the stress response in the rotor blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Also, the resistance of the rotor blades, in terms of their tensile strengths, exhibits a natural variability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Given the increasing size of production wind turbines, blade failures are increasingly relevant when assessing public safety risks from wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The most common failure is the loss of a blade or part thereof.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This has to be considered in the design.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In light of these failure modes and increasingly larger blade systems, researchers seek cost-effective materials with higher strength-to-mass ratios.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wood and canvas sails were used on early windmills due to their low price, availability, and ease of manufacture.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] These materials, however, require frequent maintenance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wood and canvas construction limits the airfoil shape to a flat plate, which has a relatively high ratio of drag to force captured (low aerodynamic efficiency) compared to solid airfoils.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Construction of solid airfoil designs requires inflexible materials such as metals or composites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Advances in turbine blade materials mirrored the progression of materials science as a broader subject.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The first large turbine blades were predominantly made from metals like steel and aluminum due to their availability and robustness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, their heavy weight and low flexibility restricted turbine size and decreased efficiency, requiring more energy to maintain blade rotation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The wind energy sector eventually moved onto lighter materials, namely fiberglass, a marked improvement over the excessive weight of metals.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] However, fiberglass possessed its own set of disadvantages, notably durability and sustainability issues.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] They were susceptible to environmental damages including UV radiation and moisture, leading to delamination and loss of structural integrity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Additionally, fiberglass is difficult to recycle, making the end-of-life impact of fiberglass blades quite high.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As a response to these challenges, the wind energy industry looked to carbon fiber as a blade material, the specific stiffness and durability of which are greater than both metal and carbon fiber.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The superior stiffness-to-weight ratio allows for the use of larger blades, increasing efficiency (see **size** section).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In recent research, bio-based composites and nanostructure enhancements have been utilized to further reduce weight and increase strength and stiffness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The majority of commercialized wind turbine blades are made from fiber-reinforced polymers (FRPs), which are composites consisting of a polymer matrix and fibers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The long fibers provide longitudinal stiffness and strength, and the matrix provides fracture toughness, delamination strength, out-of-plane strength, and stiffness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Material indices based on maximizing power efficiency, high fracture toughness, fatigue resistance, and thermal stability are highest for glass and carbon fiber reinforced plastics (GFRPs and CFRPs).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In turbine blades, matrices such as thermosets or thermoplastics are used; as of 2017, thermosets are more common.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] These allow for the fibers to be bound together and add toughness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Thermosets make up 80% of the market, as they have lower viscosity, and also allow for low-temperature cure, both features contributing to ease of processing during manufacture.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Thermoplastics offer recyclability that the thermosets do not, however their processing temperature and viscosity are much higher, limiting the product size and consistency, which are both important for large blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Fracture toughness is higher for thermoplastics, but the fatigue behavior is worse.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] blades of Siemens SWT-2.3-101 wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Manufacturing blades in the 40 to 50-metre range involves proven fiberglass composite fabrication techniques.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Manufacturers such as Nordex and GE Wind use an infusion process.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Other manufacturers vary this technique, some including carbon and wood with fiberglass in an epoxy matrix.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Other options include pre-impregnated ("prepreg") fiberglass and vacuum-assisted resin transfer moulding.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Each of these options uses a glass-fiber reinforced polymer composite constructed with differing complexity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Perhaps the largest issue with open-mould, wet systems is the emissions associated with the volatile organic compounds ("VOCs") released.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Preimpregnated materials and resin infusion techniques contain all VOCs, however these contained processes have their challenges, because the production of thick laminates necessary for structural components becomes more difficult.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] In particular, the preform resin permeability dictates the maximum laminate thickness; also, bleeding is required to eliminate voids and ensure proper resin distribution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] One solution to resin distribution is to use partially impregnated fiberglass.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] During evacuation, the dry fabric provides a path for airflow and, once heat and pressure are applied, the resin may flow into the dry region, resulting in an evenly impregnated laminate structure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Epoxy-based composites have environmental, production, and cost advantages over other resin systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Epoxies also allow shorter cure cycles, increased durability, and improved surface finish.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Prepreg operations further reduce processing time over wet lay-up systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As turbine blades passed 60 metres, infusion techniques became more prevalent, because traditional resin transfer moulding injection times are too long compared to resin set-up time, limiting laminate thickness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Injection forces resin through a thicker ply stack, thus depositing the resin in the laminate structure before gelation occurs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Specialized epoxy resins have been developed to customize lifetimes and viscosity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Carbon fiber-reinforced load-bearing spars can reduce weight and increase stiffness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Using carbon fibers in 60-metre turbine blades is estimated to reduce total blade mass by 38% and decrease cost by 14% compared to 100% fiberglass.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Carbon fibers have the added benefit of reducing the thickness of fiberglass laminate sections, further addressing the problems associated with resin wetting of thick lay-up sections.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind turbines benefit from the trend of decreasing carbon fiber costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Although glass and carbon fibers have many optimal qualities, their downsides include the fact that high filler fraction (10-70 wt%) causes increased density as well as microscopic defects and voids that can lead to premature failure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) can reinforce polymer-based nanocomposites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] CNTs can be grown or deposited on the fibers or added into polymer resins as a matrix for FRP structures.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Using nanoscale CNTs as filler instead of traditional microscale filler (such as glass or carbon fibers) results in CNT/polymer nanocomposites, for which the properties can be changed significantly at low filler contents (typically < 5 wt%).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] They have low density and improve the elastic modulus, strength, and fracture toughness of the polymer matrix.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The addition of CNTs to the matrix also reduces the propagation of interlaminar cracks.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Research on a low-cost carbon fiber (LCCF) at Oak Ridge National Laboratory gained attention in 2020, because it can mitigate the structural damage from lightning strikes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] On glass fiber wind turbines, lightning strike protection (LSP) is usually added on top, but this is effectively deadweight in terms of structural contribution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Using conductive carbon fiber can avoid adding this extra weight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A significant concern in materials criteria for a turbine blade is its manufacturing and end-of-life environmental impact, as well its recyclability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] While there are methods for manufacturing of fiberglass and carbon fiber composites into turbine blades have a lower carbon footprint than aluminum, for example, they still have a noticeable impact (30–100 kg CO2 equivalent per kg).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Additionally, fiberglass is incredibly difficult to recycle and carbon fiber composites, while possible to recycle, require additional research to yield fibers that are suitable for reusing as turbine materials (as opposed to the fibers being so degraded that they are only suitable for downcycling).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The development of bio-composite materials with sufficient mechanical properties aims to address these issues.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Bio-composite materials use natural fibers and fillers as reinforcement instead of synthetic glass or carbon fibers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Approaches vary from partial to complete replacement of synthetics, with varying levels of success.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Unfortunately, plant-based natural fibers, while having extremely low environmental impact, possess issues in their structural properties.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Namely, they have high cellulosic content and large oxygen reaction sites, both of which contribute to issues in mechanical and thermal performance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As such, other natural fibers, such as non-moisture attractive basalt, have become the focus of bio-composite research.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Some polymer composites feature self-healing properties.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Since the blades of the turbine form cracks from fatigue due to repetitive cyclic stresses, self-healing polymers are attractive for this application, because they can improve reliability and buffer various defects such as delamination.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Embedding paraffin wax-coated copper wires in a fiber reinforced polymer creates a network of tubes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Using a catalyst, these tubes and dicyclopentadiene (DCPD) then react to form a thermosetting polymer, which repairs the cracks as they form in the material.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As of 2019, this approach is not yet commercial.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Further improvement is possible through the use of carbon nanofibers (CNFs) in the blade coatings.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A major problem in desert environments is erosion of the leading edges of blades by sand-laden wind, which increases roughness and decreases aerodynamic performance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The particle erosion resistance of fiber-reinforced polymers is poor when compared to metallic materials and elastomers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Replacing glass fiber with CNF on the composite surface greatly improves erosion resistance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] CNFs provide good electrical conductivity (important for lightning strikes), high damping ratio, and good impact-friction resistance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] For wind turbines, especially those offshore, or in wet environments, base surface erosion also occurs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] For example, in cold climates, ice can build up on the blades and increase roughness.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] At high speeds, this same erosion impact can occur from rainwater.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] A useful coating must have good adhesion, temperature tolerance, weather tolerance (to resist erosion from salt, rain, sand, etc.), mechanical strength, ultraviolet light tolerance, and have anti-icing and flame retardant properties.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Along with this, the coating should be cheap and environmentally friendly.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Super hydrophobic surfaces (SHS) cause water droplets to bead, and roll off the blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] SHS prevents ice formation, up to -25 C, as it changes the ice formation process.; specifically, small ice islands form on SHS, as opposed to a large ice front.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Further, due to the lowered surface area from the hydrophobic surface, aerodynamic forces on the blade allow these islands to glide off the blade, maintaining proper aerodynamics.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] SHS can be combined with heating elements to further prevent ice formation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Lightning damage over the course of a 25-year lifetime goes from surface level scorching and cracking of the laminate material, to ruptures in the blade or full separation in the adhesives that hold the blade together.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] It is most common to observe lightning strikes on the tips of the blades, especially in rainy weather due to embedded copper wiring.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The most common method countermeasure, especially in non-conducting blade materials like GFRPs and CFRPs, is to add lightning "arresters", which are metallic wires that ground the blade, skipping the blades and gearbox entirely.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Wind turbine blades typically require repair after 2–5 years.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Notable causes of blade damage comes from manufacturing defects, transportation, assembly, installation, lightning strikes, environmental wear, thermal cycling, leading edge erosion, or fatigue.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Due to composite blade material and function, repair techniques found in aerospace applications often apply or provide a basis for basic repairs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Depending on the nature of the damage, the approach of blade repairs can vary.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Erosion repair and protection includes coatings, tapes, or shields.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Structural repairs require bonding or fastening new material to the damaged area.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Nonstructural matrix cracks and delaminations require fills and seals or resin injections.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] If ignored, minor cracks or delaminations can propagate and create structural damage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] After the past few decades of rapid wind expansion across the globe, wind turbines are aging.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This aging brings operation and maintenance(O&M) costs along with it, increasing as turbines approach their end of life.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] If damages to blades are not caught in time, power production and blade lifespan are decreased.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Estimates project that 20-25% of the total levelized cost per kWh produced stems from blade O&M alone.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The Global Wind Energy Council (GWEC) predicted that wind energy will supply 28.5% of global energy by 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] This requires a newer and larger fleet of more efficient turbines and the corresponding decommissioning of older ones.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Based on a European Wind Energy Association study, in 2010 between 110 and 140 kilotonnes of composites were consumed to manufacture blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The majority of the blade material ends up as waste and requires recycling or downcycling.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] As of 2020, most end-of-use blades are stored or sent to landfills rather than recycled.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] It is also important to note that recent studies predict that nearly 52,000 tons of turbine blades are to be decommissioned every year until 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Typically, glass-fiber-reinforced polymers (GFRPs) comprise around 70% of the laminate material in the blade.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] GFRPs are not combustible and so hinder the incineration of combustible materials.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The following methods are the major EOL paths for turbine blades, with methods varying depending on whether individual fibers are to be recovered and the requisite temperature/catalysts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] Start-up company Global Fiberglass Solutions claimed in 2020 that it had a method to process blades into pellets and fiber boards for use in flooring and walls.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p01] The company started producing samples at a plant in Sweetwater, Texas.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Wind velocities increase at higher altitudes due to surface aerodynamic drag (by land or water surfaces) and air viscosity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The variation in velocity with altitude, called wind shear, is most dramatic near the surface.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Typically, the variation follows the wind profile power law, which predicts that wind speed rises proportionally to the seventh root of altitude.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Doubling the altitude of a turbine, then, increases the expected wind speeds by 10% and the expected power by 34%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] To avoid buckling, doubling the tower height generally requires doubling the tower diameter, increasing the amount of material by a factor of at least four.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As of July 2025, the world's tallest wind turbine, at 300 metres (980 ft) hub height with 3.8 MW capacity, was under construction in Germany.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] During the night, or when the atmosphere becomes stable, wind speed close to the ground usually subsides whereas at turbine hub altitude it does not decrease that much or may even increase.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As a result, the wind speed is higher and a turbine will produce more power than expected from the 1/7 power law: doubling the altitude may increase wind speed by 20% to 60%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A stable atmosphere is caused by radiative cooling of the surface and is common in a temperate climate: it usually occurs when there is a (partly) clear sky at night.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] When the (high altitude) wind is strong (a 10-meter wind speed higher than approximately 6 to 7 m/s) the stable atmosphere is disrupted because of friction turbulence and the atmosphere turns neutral.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A daytime atmosphere is either neutral (no net radiation; usually with strong winds and heavy clouding) or unstable (rising air because of ground heating—by the sun).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The 1/7 power law is a good approximation of the wind profile.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Indiana was rated as having a wind capacity of 30,000 MW, but by raising the expected turbine height from 50 m to 70 m raised the wind capacity to 40,000 MW, and could be double that at 100 m.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] For HAWTs, tower heights approximately two to three times the blade length balance material costs of the tower against better utilisation of the more expensive active components.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Road restrictions make tower transport with a diameter of more than 4.3 m difficult.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Swedish analyses showed that the bottom wing tip must be at least 30 m above the tree tops.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A 3 MW turbine may increase output from 5,000 MWh to 7,700 MWh per year by rising from 80 to 125 meters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A tower profile made of connected shells rather than cylinders can have a larger diameter and still be transportable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A 100 m prototype tower with TC bolted 18 mm 'plank' shells at the wind turbine test center Høvsøre in Denmark was certified by Det Norske Veritas, with a Siemens nacelle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Shell elements can be shipped in standard 12 m shipping containers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As of 2003, typical modern wind turbine installations used 65 metres (213 ft) towers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Height is typically limited by the availability of cranes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] This led to proposals for "partially self-erecting wind turbines" that, for a given available crane, allow taller towers that locate a turbine in stronger and steadier winds, and "self-erecting wind turbines" that could be installed without cranes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Currently, the majority of wind turbines are supported by conical tubular steel towers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] These towers represent 30% – 65% of the turbine weight and therefore account for a large percentage of transport costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The use of lighter tower materials could reduce the overall transport and construction cost, as long as stability is maintained.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Higher grade S500 steel costs 20%-25% more than S355 steel (standard structural steel), but it requires 30% less material because of its improved strength.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Therefore, replacing wind turbine towers with S500 steel offer savings in weight and cost.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Another disadvantage of conical steel towers is meeting the requirements of wind turbines taller than 90 meters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] High performance concrete may increase tower height and increase lifetime.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A hybrid of prestressed concrete and steel improves performance over standard tubular steel at tower heights of 120 meters.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Concrete also allows small precast sections to be assembled on site.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] One downside of concrete towers is the higher CO 2 emissions during concrete production.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] However, the overall environmental impact should be positive if concrete towers can double the wind turbine lifetime.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Wood is another alternative: a 100-metre tower supporting a 1.5 MW turbine operates in Germany.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The wood tower shares the same transportation benefits of the segmented steel shell tower, but without the steel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A 2 MW turbine on a wooden tower started operating in Sweden in 2023.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Another approach is to form the tower on site via spiral welding rolled sheet steel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Towers of any height and diameter can be formed this way, eliminating restrictions driven by transport requirements.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The developer claims 80% labor savings over conventional approaches.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Grid-connected wind turbines, until the 1970s, were fixed-speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As recently as 2003, nearly all grid-connected wind turbines operated at constant speed (synchronous generators) or within a few percent of constant speed (induction generators).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As of 2011, many turbines used fixed-speed induction generators (FSIG).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] By then, most newly connected turbines were variable speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Early control systems were designed for peak power extraction, also called maximum power point tracking—they attempted to pull the maximum power from a given wind turbine under the current wind conditions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The generator produces alternating current (AC).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The most common method in large modern turbines is to use a doubly fed induction generator directly connected to the grid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Some turbines drive an AC/AC converter—which converts the AC to direct current (DC) with a rectifier and then back to AC with an inverter—in order to match grid frequency and phase.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A useful technique to connect a PMSG (Permanent Magnet Synchronous Generator) to the grid is via a back-to-back converter.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Control schemes can achieve unity power factor in the connection to the grid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] In that way the wind turbine does not consume reactive power, which is the most common problem with turbines that use induction machines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] This leads to a more stable power system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Moreover, with different control schemes a PMSG turbine can provide or consume reactive power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] So, it can work as a dynamic capacitor/inductor bank to help with grid stability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Reactive power regulation consists of one PI controller in order to achieve operation with unity power factor (i.e.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] IdN has to be regulated to reach zero at steady-state (IdNref = 0).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The complete system of the grid side converter and the cascaded PI controller loops is displayed in the figure.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As wind turbine usage has increased, so have companies that assist in the planning and construction of wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Most often, turbine parts are shipped via sea or rail, and then via truck to the installation site.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Due to the massive size of the components involved, companies usually need to obtain transportation permits and ensure that the chosen trucking route is free of potential obstacles such as overpasses, bridges, and narrow roads.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Groups known as "reconnaissance teams" will scout the way up to a year in advance as they identify problematic roads, cut down trees, and relocate utility poles.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Turbine blades continue to increase in size, sometimes necessitating brand new logistical plans, as previously used routes may not allow a larger blade.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Specialized vehicles known as Schnabel trailers are custom-designed to load and transport turbine sections: tower sections can be loaded without a crane and the rear end of the trailer is steerable, allowing for easier maneuvering.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Wind turbines, by their nature, are very tall, slender structures, and this can cause a number of issues when the structural design of the foundations are considered.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The foundations for a conventional engineering structure are designed mainly to transfer the vertical load (dead weight) to the ground, generally allowing comparatively unsophisticated arrangement to be used.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] However, in the case of wind turbines, the force of the wind's interaction with the rotor at the top of the tower creates a strong tendency to tip the wind turbine over.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] This loading regime causes large moment loads to be applied to the foundations of a wind turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] As a result, considerable attention needs to be given when designing the footings to ensure that the foundation will resist this tipping tendency.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] One of the most common foundations for offshore wind turbines is the monopile, a single large-diameter (4 to 6 metres) tubular steel pile driven to a depth of 5-6 times the diameter of the pile into the seabed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The cohesion of the soil, and friction between the pile and the soil provide the necessary structural support for the wind turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] In onshore turbines the most common type of foundation is a gravity foundation, where a large mass of concrete spread out over a large area is used to resist the turbine loads.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Wind turbine size & type, wind conditions and soil conditions at the site are all determining factors in the design of the foundation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Prestressed piles or rock anchors are alternative foundation designs that use much less concrete and steel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] A wind turbine is a complex and integrated system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Structural elements comprise the majority of the weight and cost.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] All parts of the structure must be inexpensive, lightweight, durable, and manufacturable, surviving variable loading and environmental conditions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Turbine systems with fewer failures require less maintenance, are lighter and last longer, reducing costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The major parts of a turbine divide as: tower 22%, blades 18%, gearbox 14%, generator 8%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Turbine design specifications contain a power curve and availability guarantee.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] The wind resource assessment makes it possible to calculate commercial viability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Typical operating temperature range is −20 to 40 °C (−4 to 104 °F).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] In areas with extreme climate (like Inner Mongolia or Rajasthan) climate-specific versions are required.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] Wind turbines can be designed and validated according to IEC 61400 standards.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] RDS-PP (Reference Designation System for Power Plants) is a standardized system used worldwide to create structured hierarchy of wind turbine components.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine-design-p02] This facilitates turbine maintenance and operation cost, and is used during all stages of a turbine creation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A **wind turbine** is a device that converts the kinetic energy of wind into electrical energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] As of 2024, hundreds of thousands of large turbines, in installations known as wind farms, were generating over 1,136 gigawatts of power, with 117 GW added each year.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines are an increasingly important source of intermittent renewable energy, and are used in many countries to lower energy costs and reduce reliance on fossil fuels.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] One study claimed that, as of 2009, wind had the "lowest relative greenhouse gas emissions, the least water consumption demands and the most favorable social impacts" compared to photovoltaic, hydro, geothermal, coal and gas energy sources.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines are manufactured in a wide range of sizes, with either horizontal or vertical axes, though horizontal is most common.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Commercial power production horizontal-axis turbines usually have three blades, upwind of their towers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Blades are most commonly made of glass fiber composites, but carbon fiber which is stiffer, stronger, and less dense is also used.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Smaller wind turbines are used for applications such as battery charging and remote devices such as traffic warning signs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Larger turbines can contribute to a domestic power supply while selling unused power back to the utility supplier via the electrical grid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines produce among the cheapest renewable energy, and are clean, emitting no greenhouse gases.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] They have a significant environmental impact such as on wildlife, but this can be mitigated.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The power produced varies with the wind, not with demand, so it is an unreliable source of energy unless energy storage is available.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The windwheel of Hero of Alexandria (10–70 CE) marks one of the first recorded instances of wind powering a machine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, the first known practical wind power plants were built in Sistan, an Eastern province of Persia (now Iran), from the 7th century.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These panemone windmills were vertical-axle windmills, which had long vertical drive shafts with rectangular blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Made of six to twelve sails covered in reed matting or cloth material, these wind turbines were used to grind grain or draw up water, and were used in the gristmilling and sugarcane industries.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind power first appeared in Europe during the Middle Ages.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The first historical records of their use in England date to the 11th and 12th centuries; there are reports of German crusaders taking their windmill-making skills to Syria around 1190.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] By the 15th century, Dutch windpumps were in use to drain low-lying land.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Vertical-axis wind turbines were described by Croatian inventor Fausto Veranzio in his book *Machinae Novae* (1595).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The first electricity-generating wind turbine was installed by the Austrian Josef Friedländer at the Vienna International Electrical Exhibition in 1883.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It was a Halladay wind turbine for driving a dynamo.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Friedländer's 6.6 m (22 ft) diameter Halladay "wind motor" was supplied by U.S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind Engine & Pump Co. of Batavia, Illinois.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The 3.7 kW (5 hp) wind turbine drove a dynamo at ground level that fed electricity into a series of batteries.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The batteries powered various electrical tools and lamps, as well as a threshing machine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Friedländer's wind turbine and its accessories were prominently installed at the north entrance to the main exhibition hall ("Rotunde") in the Vienna Prater.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In July 1887, Scottish academic James Blyth installed a battery-charging machine to light his holiday home in Marykirk, Scotland.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Some months later, American inventor Charles F.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Brush was able to build the first automatically operated wind turbine after consulting local University professors and his colleagues Jacob S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Gibbs and Brinsley Coleberd and successfully getting the blueprints peer-reviewed for electricity production.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Although Blyth's turbine was considered uneconomical in the United Kingdom, electricity generation by wind turbines was more cost effective in countries with widely scattered populations.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In Denmark by 1900, there were about 2500 windpumps and windmills, producing an estimated combined peak mechanical power of about 30 megawatts (MW).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The largest machines were on 24-metre (79 ft) towers with four-bladed 23-metre (75 ft) diameter rotors.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] By 1908, there were 72 wind-driven electric generators operating in the United States from 5 kilowatts (kW) to 25 kW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Around the time of World War I, American wind turbine makers were producing 100,000 each year, mostly for water-pumping.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] By the 1930s, use of wind turbines in rural areas was declining as the distribution system extended to those areas.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A forerunner of modern horizontal-axis wind generators was in service at Yalta, USSR, in 1931.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This was a 100 kW generator on a 30-meter (98 ft) tower.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It was reported to have an annual capacity factor of 32 percent, not much different from current wind machines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In the autumn of 1941, the first megawatt-class wind turbine was synchronized to a utility grid in Vermont.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The Smith–Putnam wind turbine only ran for about five years before one of the blades snapped off.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The unit was not repaired, because of a shortage of materials during the war.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The first utility grid-connected wind turbine to operate in the UK was built by John Brown & Company in 1951 in the Orkney Islands.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In the early 1970s, however, anti-nuclear protests in Denmark spurred artisan mechanics to develop microturbines of 22 kW despite declines in the industry.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Organizing owners into associations and co-operatives led to the lobbying of the government and utilities and provided incentives for larger turbines throughout the 1980s and later.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Local activists in Germany, nascent turbine manufacturers in Spain, and large investors in the United States in the early 1990s then lobbied for policies that stimulated the industry in those countries.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It has been argued that expanding the use of wind power will lead to increasing geopolitical competition over critical materials for wind turbines, such as rare earth elements neodymium, praseodymium, and dysprosium.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, this perspective has been critically dismissed for failing to relay how most wind turbines do not use permanent magnets and for underestimating the power of economic incentives for the expanded production of these minerals.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind power density (WPD) is a quantitative measure of wind energy available at any location.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It is the mean power available per swept area of a turbine, and is calculated for different heights above ground.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Calculation of wind power density includes the effect of wind velocity and air density.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines are classified by the wind speed they are designed for, from class I to class III, with A to C referring to the turbulence intensity of the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Conservation of mass requires that the mass of air entering and exiting a turbine must be equal.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Likewise, the conservation of energy requires the energy given to the turbine from incoming wind to be equal to that of the combination of the energy in the outgoing wind and the energy converted to electrical energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Since outgoing wind will still possess some kinetic energy, there must be a maximum proportion of the input energy that is available to be converted to electrical energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Accordingly, Betz's law gives the maximal achievable extraction of wind power by a wind turbine, known as Betz's coefficient, as 16⁄27 (59.3%) of the rate at which the kinetic energy of the air arrives at the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The maximum theoretical power output of a wind machine is thus 16⁄27 times the rate at which kinetic energy of the air arrives at the effective disk area of the machine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind-to-rotor efficiency (including rotor blade friction and drag) are among the factors affecting the final price of wind power.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Further inefficiencies, such as gearbox, generator, and converter losses, reduce the power delivered by a wind turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] To protect components from undue wear, extracted power is held constant above the rated operating speed as theoretical power increases as the cube of wind speed, further reducing theoretical efficiency.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In 2001, commercial utility-connected turbines delivered 75% to 80% of the Betz limit of power extractable from the wind, at rated operating speed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Efficiency can decrease slightly over time, one of the main reasons being dust and insect carcasses on the blades, which alter the aerodynamic profile and essentially reduce the lift to drag ratio of the airfoil.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Analysis of 3128 wind turbines older than 10 years in Denmark showed that half of the turbines had no decrease, while the other half saw a production decrease of 1.2% per year.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In general, more stable and constant weather conditions (most notably wind speed) result in an average of 15% greater efficiency than that of a wind turbine in unstable weather conditions, thus allowing up to a 7% increase in wind speed under stable conditions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This is due to a faster recovery wake and greater flow entrainment that occur in conditions of higher atmospheric stability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, wind turbine wakes have been found to recover faster under unstable atmospheric conditions as opposed to a stable environment.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Different materials have varying effects on the efficiency of wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In an Ege University experiment, three wind turbines, each with three blades with a diameter of one meter, were constructed with blades made of different materials: A glass and glass/carbon epoxy, glass/carbon, and glass/polyester.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] When tested, the results showed that the materials with higher overall masses had a greater friction moment and thus a lower power coefficient.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The air velocity is the major contributor to the turbine efficiency.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This is the reason for the importance of choosing the right location.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The wind velocity will be high near the shore because of the temperature difference between the land and the ocean.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Another option is to place turbines on mountain ridges.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The higher the wind turbine will be, the higher the wind velocity on average.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A windbreak can also increase the wind velocity near the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines can rotate about either a horizontal or a vertical axis, the former being both older and more common.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] They can also include blades or be bladeless.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Household-size vertical designs produce less power and are less common.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Large three-bladed horizontal-axis wind turbines (HAWT) with the blades upwind of the tower (*i.e.* blades facing the incoming wind) produce the overwhelming majority of wind power in the world today.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These turbines have the main rotor shaft and electrical generator at the top of a tower and must be pointed into the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Small turbines are pointed by a simple wind vane, while large turbines generally use a wind sensor coupled with a yaw system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Most have a gearbox, which turns the slow rotation of the blades into a quicker rotation that is more suitable to drive an electrical generator.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Some turbines use a different type of generator suited to slower rotational speed input.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These do not need a gearbox and are called direct-drive, meaning they couple the rotor directly to the generator with no gearbox in between.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] There is also the pseudo direct drive mechanism, which has some advantages over the permanent magnet direct drive mechanism.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Most horizontal-axis turbines have their rotors upwind of the supporting tower.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Downwind machines have been built, because they don't need an additional mechanism for keeping them in line with the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In high winds, downwind blades can also be designed to bend more than upwind ones, which reduces their swept area and thus their wind resistance, mitigating risk during gales.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Despite these advantages, upwind designs are preferred, because the pulsing change in loading from the wind as each blade passes behind the supporting tower can cause damage to the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Turbines used in wind farms for commercial production of electric power are usually three-bladed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These have low torque ripple, which contributes to good reliability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The blades are usually colored white for daytime visibility by aircraft and range in length from 20 to 80 meters (66 to 262 ft).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The size and height of turbines increase year by year.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Offshore wind turbines are built up to 26 MW today and have a blade length up to 153 meters (502 ft), while onshore turbines reach up to 15 MW of capacity and 131 meters (430 ft) of blade length.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The average hub height of horizontal-axis wind turbines is 103 meters (338 ft) for onshore turbines in the U.S. and 124 meters (407 ft) for global offshore turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Vertical-axis wind turbines (or VAWTs) have the main rotor shaft arranged vertically.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] One advantage of this arrangement is that the turbine does not need to be pointed into the wind to be effective, which is an advantage on a site where the wind direction is highly variable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It is also an advantage when the turbine is integrated into a building because it is inherently less steerable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Also, the generator and gearbox can be placed near the ground, using a direct drive from the rotor assembly to the ground-based gearbox, improving accessibility for maintenance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, these designs produce much less energy averaged over time, which is a major drawback.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Vertical turbine designs have much lower efficiency than standard horizontal designs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] When a turbine is mounted on a rooftop the building generally redirects wind over the roof and this can double the wind speed at the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] If the height of a rooftop-mounted turbine tower is about half of the building height it is near the optimum for maximum wind energy and minimum wind turbulence.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] While wind speeds within the built environment are generally much lower than at exposed rural sites, noise may be a concern and an existing structure must be able to resist the additional stress.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] There are several subtypes of the vertical-axis design, including the Darrieus wind turbine, also known as an eggbeater turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These were named for Georges Jean Marie Darrieus who patented a design in the 1920s.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] They have good efficiency, but produce large torque ripple and cyclical stress on the tower, which contributes to poor reliability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The torque ripple is reduced by using three or more blades, which results in greater solidity of the rotor.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The giromill is a subtype of Darrieus turbine with straight blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The cycloturbine variety has variable pitch to reduce the torque pulsation and is self-starting.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The advantages of variable pitch are high starting torque; a wide, relatively flat torque curve; a higher coefficient of performance; more efficient operation in turbulent winds; and a lower blade speed ratio, which lowers blade bending stresses.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Straight, V, or curved blades may be used.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The Savonius wind turbine are drag-type devices with two (or more) scoops that are used in anemometers, *Flettner* vents (commonly seen on bus and van roofs), and in some high-reliability low-efficiency power turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] They are always self-starting if there are at least three scoops.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Twisted Savonius is a modified Savonius with long helical scoops to provide smooth torque.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This is often used as a rooftop wind turbine and has even been adapted for ships.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Airborne wind turbines consist of wings or a small aircraft tethered to the ground.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] They are useful for reaching faster winds above which traditional turbines can operate.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] There are prototypes in operation in east Africa.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A floating wind turbine is an offshore turbine supported by a floating platform.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] By having them float, they can to be installed in deeper water, allowing more of them; by having them further out of sight from land, they may create less public concern about their visual impact.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines convert wind energy to electrical energy for distribution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A 1.5 (MW) wind turbine of a type frequently seen in the United States has a tower 80 meters (260 ft) high.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The rotor assembly (blades and hub) measures about 80 meters (260 ft) in diameter.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The nacelle, which contains the generator, is 15.24 meters (50.0 ft) and weighs around 300 tons.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Due to data transmission problems, structural health monitoring of wind turbines is usually performed using several accelerometers and strain gages attached to the nacelle to monitor the gearbox and equipment.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Currently, digital image correlation and stereophotogrammetry are used to measure dynamics of wind turbine blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These methods usually measure displacement and strain to identify location of defects.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Dynamic characteristics of non-rotating wind turbines have been measured using digital image correlation and photogrammetry.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Three dimensional point tracking has also been used to measure rotating dynamics of wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Generally, efficiency increases along with turbine blade lengths.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The blades must be stiff, strong, durable, light and resistant to fatigue.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Materials with these properties include composites such as polyester and epoxy, while glass fiber and carbon fiber have been used for the reinforcing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Construction may involve manual layup or injection molding.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Retrofitting existing turbines with larger blades reduces the task and risks of redesign.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] While turbines have an average lifespan of 30 years, blades and gearboxes usually last up to 25 years.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Materials commonly used in wind turbine blades are described below.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The stiffness of composites is determined by the stiffness of fibers and their volume content.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Typically, E-glass fibers are used as main reinforcement in the composites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Typically, the glass/epoxy composites for wind turbine blades contain up to 75% glass by weight.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This increases the stiffness, tensile and compression strength.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A promising composite material is glass fiber with modified compositions like S-glass, R-glass etc.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Other glass fibers developed by Owens Corning are ECRGLAS, Advantex and WindStrand.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Carbon fiber has more tensile strength, higher stiffness and lower density than glass fiber.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] An ideal candidate for these properties is the spar cap, a structural element of a blade that experiences high tensile loading.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A 100-metre (330 ft) glass fiber blade could weigh up to 50 tonnes (110,000 lb), while using carbon fiber in the spar saves 20% to 30% weight, about 15 tonnes (33,000 lb).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Instead of making wind turbine blade reinforcements from pure glass or pure carbon, hybrid designs trade weight for cost.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] For example, for an 8-metre (26 ft) blade, a full replacement by carbon fiber would save 80% of weight but increase costs by 150%, while a 30% replacement would save 50% of weight and increase costs by 90%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Hybrid reinforcement materials include E-glass/carbon, E-glass/aramid.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The current longest blade by LM Wind Power is made of carbon/glass hybrid composites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] More research is needed about the optimal composition of materials.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Additions of small amount (0.5 weight %) of nanoreinforcement (carbon nanotubes or nanoclay) in the polymer matrix of composites, fiber sizing or inter-laminar layers can improve fatigue resistance, shear or compressive strength, and fracture toughness of the composites by 30% to 80%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Research has also shown that incorporating small amounts of carbon nanotubes (CNT) can increase the lifetime up to 1500%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The global weighted average capital cost of a wind turbine was approximately $2,324 per kilowatt in 2010.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] As of 2024, this figure had fallen to $1,041 per kilowatt of nameplate capacity, reflecting a consistent year-on-year decline of around 12%.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Home wind turbines are significantly cheaper, with costs as little as $700 for a small 400 W turbine (non-including installation costs) in the U.S.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The levelized cost of energy (LCOE) of wind turbines, or the average minimum price per unit of energy a power plant must receive to break even over its lifetime, as of 2025 spanned from $25 per MWh in China to $70 per MWh in Vietnam, and averaged globally around $50–60 per MWh.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The MENA region reported the lowest average LCOE, with the 2024 Al Ghat wind farm project in Saudi Arabia setting a global record of only $15.66 per MWh.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] For the wind turbine blades, while the material cost is much higher for hybrid glass/carbon fiber blades than all-glass fiber blades, labor costs can be lower.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Using carbon fiber allows simpler designs that use less raw material.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The chief manufacturing process in blade fabrication is the layering of plies.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Thinner blades allow reducing the number of layers and thus the labor and in some cases, equate to the cost of labor for glass fiber blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Offshore has significantly higher installation costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The global weighted average total installation costs for offshore turbines were $2,852 per kW in 2024, having fallen by 48% from the 2010 costs of $5,518 per kW.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbine parts other than the rotor blades (including the rotor hub, gearbox, frame, and tower) are largely made of steel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Smaller turbines (as well as megawatt-scale Enercon turbines) have begun using aluminum alloys for these components to make turbines lighter and more efficient.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This trend may grow if fatigue and strength properties can be improved.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Pre-stressed concrete has been increasingly used for the material of the tower, but still requires much reinforcing steel to meet the strength requirement of the turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Additionally, step-up gearboxes are being increasingly replaced with variable speed generators, which requires magnetic materials.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Modern turbines use some two tons of copper for wiring, generators, transformers, and grounding systems due to its exceptional electrical conductivity and durability.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] As of 2018, global production of wind turbines use 450,000 tonnes (990 million pounds) of copper per year.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] As of 2025, copper intensity ranges between 650 and 6,200 kg per MW of capacity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A 2015 study of the material consumption trends and requirements for wind energy in Europe found that bigger turbines have a higher consumption of precious metals but lower material input per kW generated.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The material consumption and stock at that time was compared to input materials for various onshore system sizes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In all EU countries, the estimates for 2020 doubled the values consumed in 2009.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These countries would need to expand their resources to meet the estimated demand for 2020.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] For example, the EU had 3% of world supply of fluorspar, and it would require 14% by 2020.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Globally, the main exporting countries are South Africa, Mexico, and China.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This is similar to other critical and valuable materials required for energy systems such as magnesium, silver and indium.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] While the levels of recycling of these materials are very low, focusing on their circularity could alleviate supply.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Since most of these valuable materials are also used in other emerging technologies, like light emitting diodes (LEDs), photo voltaics (PVs) and liquid crystal displays (LCDs), their demand is expected to grow.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A 2011 study by the United States Geological Survey estimated resources required to fulfill the US commitment to supplying 20% of its electricity from wind power by 2030.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It did not consider requirements for small turbines or offshore turbines because those were not common in 2008 when the study was done.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Common materials such as cast iron, steel and concrete would increase by 2%–3% compared to 2008.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Between 110,000 and 115,000 metric tons of fiber glass would be required per year, a 14% increase.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Rare-earth metal use would not increase much compared to available supply, however rare-earth metals that are also used for other technologies such as batteries which are increasing its global demand need to be taken into account.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Land required would be 50,000 square kilometers onshore and 11,000 offshore.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] This would not be a problem in the US due to its vast area and because the same land can be used for farming.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A greater challenge would be the variability and transmission to areas of high demand.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Permanent magnets for wind turbine generators contain rare-earth metals such as neodymium (Nd), praseodymium (Pr), terbium (Tb), and dysprosium (Dy).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Systems that use magnetic direct drive turbines require greater amounts of rare-earth metals.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Therefore, an increase in wind turbine manufacture would increase the demand for these resources.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] By 2035, the demand for Nd is estimated to increase by 4,000 to 18,000 tons and for Dy by 200 to 1,200 tons.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] These values are a quarter to half of current production.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, these estimates are very uncertain because technologies are developing rapidly.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Reliance on rare earth minerals for components has risked expense and price volatility as China has been main producer of rare earth minerals (96% in 2009) and was reducing its export quotas.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, in recent years, other producers have increased production and China has increased export quotas, leading to higher supply, lower cost, and greater viability of large-scale use of variable-speed generators.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Glass fiber is the most common material for reinforcement.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Its demand has grown due to growth in construction, transportation and wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Its global market might reach US$17.4 billion by 2024, compared to US$8.5 billion in 2014.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In 2014, Asia Pacific produced more than 45% of the market; now China is the largest producer.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The industry receives subsidies from the Chinese government allowing it to export cheaper to the US and Europe.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, price wars have led to anti-dumping measures such as tariffs on Chinese glass fiber.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A few localities have exploited the attention-getting nature of wind turbines by placing them on public display, either with visitor centers around their bases, or with viewing areas farther away.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The wind turbines are generally of conventional horizontal-axis, three-bladed design and generate power to feed electrical grids, but they also serve the unconventional roles of technology demonstration, public relations, and education.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The Bahrain World Trade Center has wind turbines displayed prominently for the public.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] It is the first skyscraper to integrate wind turbines into its design.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Small wind turbines may be used for a variety of applications including on- or off-grid residences, telecom towers, offshore platforms, rural schools and clinics, remote monitoring and other purposes that require energy where there is no electric grid, or where the grid is unstable.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Small wind turbines may be as small as a fifty-watt generator for boat or caravan use.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Hybrid solar- and wind-powered units are increasingly being used for traffic signage, particularly in rural locations, since they avoid the need to lay long cables from the nearest mains connection point.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Department of Energy's National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) defines small wind turbines as those smaller than or equal to 100 kilowatts.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Small units often have direct-drive generators, direct current output, aeroelastic blades, and lifetime bearings and use a vane to point into the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] On most horizontal wind turbine farms, a spacing of about 6–10 times the rotor diameter is often upheld.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, for large wind farms, distances of about 15 rotor diameters should be more economical, taking into account typical wind turbine and land costs.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Research by John Dabiri of Caltech suggests that vertical wind turbines may be placed much more closely together so long as an alternating pattern of rotation is created allowing blades of neighbouring turbines to move in the same direction as they approach one another.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines need regular maintenance to stay reliable and available.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In the best case turbines are available to generate energy 98% of the time.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Ice accretion on turbine blades has been found to greatly reduce the efficiency of wind turbines, which is a common challenge in cold climates where in-cloud icing and freezing rain events occur.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Deicing is mainly performed by internal heating or, in some cases, by helicopters or drones spraying clean warm water on the blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Modern turbines usually have a small onboard crane for hoisting maintenance tools and minor components.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, large, heavy components like generators, gearboxes, blades, and so on are rarely replaced, and a heavy lift external crane is needed in those cases.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] If the turbine has a difficult access road, a containerized crane can be lifted up by the internal crane to provide heavier lifting.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Installation of new wind turbines can be controversial.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] An alternative is repowering, where existing wind turbines are replaced with bigger, more powerful ones, sometimes in smaller numbers while keeping or increasing capacity.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Some wind turbines which are out of use are recycled or repowered.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] 85% of turbine materials are easily reused or recycled, but the blades, made of a composite material, are more difficult to process.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Interest in recycling blades varies in different markets and depends on the waste legislation and local economics.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A challenge in recycling blades is related to the composite material, which is made of fiberglass with carbon fibers in epoxy resin, which cannot be remolded to form new composites.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind farm waste is less toxic than other garbage.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbine blades represent only a fraction of overall waste in the US, according to the wind-industry trade association, American Wind Energy Association.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Several utilities, startup companies, and researchers are developing methods for reusing or recycling blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Manufacturer Vestas has developed technology that can separate the fibers from the resin, allowing for reuse.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In Germany, wind turbine blades are commercially recycled as part of an alternative fuel mix for a cement factory.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In the United Kingdom, a project will trial cutting blades into strips for use as rebar in concrete, with the aim of reducing emissions in the construction of High Speed 2.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Used wind turbine blades have been recycled by incorporating them as part of the support structures within pedestrian bridges in Poland and Ireland.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In 2026, Chinese manufacturer Ming Yang developed the first fully recyclable wind turbine, which uses pultruded carbon fiber panels instead of fiberglass, allowing recyclers to separate the components through a chemical process.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines is one of the lowest-cost sources of renewable energy along with solar panels.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] As technology needed for wind turbines continued to improve, the prices decreased as well.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In addition, there is currently no competitive market for wind energy (though there may be in the future), because wind is a freely available natural resource, most of which is untapped.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] The main cost of small wind turbines is the purchase and installation process, which averages between $48,000 and $65,000 per installation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Usually, the total amount of energy harvested amounts to more than the cost of the turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines provide a clean energy source, use little water, emitting no greenhouse gases and no waste products during operation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Over 1,400 tonnes (1,500 short tons) of carbon dioxide per year can be eliminated by using a one-megawatt turbine instead of one megawatt of energy from a fossil fuel.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Environmental impact of wind power includes effect on wildlife, but can be mitigated if proper strategies are implemented.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Thousands of birds, including rare species, have been killed by the blades of wind turbines, though wind turbines contribute relatively insignificantly to anthropogenic avian mortality (birds killed by humans).
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind farms and nuclear power plants are responsible for between 0.3 and 0.4 bird deaths per gigawatt-hour (GWh) of electricity while fossil fuel power stations are responsible for about 5.2 fatalities per GWh.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In comparison, conventional coal-fired generators contribute significantly more to bird mortality.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A study on recorded bird populations in the United States from 2000 to 2020 found the presence of wind turbines had no significant effect on bird population numbers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Energy harnessed by wind turbines is variable, and is not a "dispatchable" source of power; its availability is based on whether the wind is blowing, not whether electricity is needed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Turbines can be placed on ridges or bluffs to maximize the access of wind they have, but this also limits the locations where they can be placed.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] In this way, wind energy is not a particularly reliable source of energy.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] However, it can form part of the energy mix, which also includes power from other sources.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Technology is also being developed to store excess energy, which can then make up for any deficits in supplies.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Wind turbines have blinking lights that warn aircraft, to avoid collisions.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] Residents living near windfarms, especially those in rural areas, have complained that the blinking lights are a bothersome form of light pollution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/wind-turbine] A light mitigation approach involves Aircraft Detection Lighting Systems (ADLSs) by which the lights are turned on, only when the ADLS's radar detects aircraft within thresholds of altitude and distance.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The **yaw system** of wind turbines is the component responsible for the orientation of the wind turbine rotor towards the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The task of orienting the rotor into the wind was a complicated issue already for historical windmills.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The first windmills able to rotate in order to "face" the wind appeared in the mid-18th century.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Their rotatable nacelles were mounted on the main structure of the windmill using primitive wooden gliding bearings lubricated with animal fat.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The necessary yawing torque was created by means of animal power, human power or even wind power (implementation of an auxiliary rotor known as fantail).
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Vertical-axis wind turbines (VAWTs) do not need a yaw system since their vertical rotors can face the wind from any direction and only their self rotation gives the blades a clear direction of the air flow.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Horizontal-axis wind turbines (HAWTs), however, need to orient their rotors into and out of the wind and they achieve that by means of passive or active yaw systems.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] HAWTs employ some sort of yaw system which can be passive or active.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Both passive and active systems have advantages and disadvantages and various design solutions (both active and passive) are being tried in order to find the optimal design for each wind turbine depending on its size, cost and purpose of operation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The active yaw systems are equipped with some sort of torque producing device able to rotate the nacelle of the wind turbine against the stationary tower based on automatic signals from wind direction sensors or manual actuation (control system override).
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The active yaw systems are considered to be the state of the art for all the modern medium and large sized wind turbines, with a few exceptions proving the rule (e.g.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The passive yaw systems utilize the wind force in order to adjust the orientation of the wind turbine rotor into the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] In their simplest form these system comprise a simple roller bearing connection between the tower and the nacelle and a tail fin mounted on the nacelle and designed in such a way that it turns the wind turbine rotor into the wind by exerting a "corrective" torque to the nacelle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Therefore, the power of the wind is responsible for the rotor rotation and the nacelle orientation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Alternatively in case of downwind turbines the tail fin is not necessary since the rotor itself is able to yaw the nacelle into the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] In the event of skew winds the "wind pressure" on the swept area causes a yawing moment around the tower axis (z-axis) which orients the rotor.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The tail fin (or wind vane) is commonly used for small wind turbines since it offers a low cost and reliable solution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] It is however unable to cope with the high moments required to yaw the nacelle of a large wind turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The self-orientation of the downwind turbine rotors however is a concept able to function even for larger wind turbines.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The French wind turbine manufacturer Vergnet has several medium and large self-orienting downwind wind turbines in production.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Passive yaw systems have to be designed in a way that the nacelle does not follow the sudden changes in wind direction with too fast a yaw movement, in order to avoid high gyroscopic loads.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Additionally the passive yaw systems with low yaw-friction are subjected to strong dynamic loads due to the periodic low amplitude yawing caused by the variation of the inertia moment during the rotor rotation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] This effect becomes more severe with the reduction of the number of blades.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] One of the main components of the yaw system is the yaw bearing.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The yaw bearing system aligns the blades to the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] It consists of the ring gear, yaw motor and the yaw bearing clamp assemblies .
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The yaw bearing can be of the roller or gliding type and it serves as a rotatable connection between the tower and the nacelle of the wind turbine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The yaw bearing should be able to handle very high loads, which apart from the weight of the nacelle and rotor (the weight of which is in the range of several tenths of tons) include also the bending moments caused by the rotor during the extraction of the kinetic energy of the wind.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The yaw drives exist only on the active yaw systems and are the means of active rotation of the wind turbine nacelle.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Each yaw drive consists of powerful electric motor (usually AC) with its electric drive and a large gearbox, which increases the torque.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The maximum static torque of the biggest yaw drives is in the range of 200.000Nm with gearbox reduction ratios in the range of 2000:1.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Consequently, the yawing of the large modern turbines is relatively slow with a 360° turn lasting several minutes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] In order to stabilize the yaw bearing against rotation a means of braking is necessary.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] One of the simplest ways to realize that task is to apply a constant small counter-torque at the yaw drives in order to eliminate the backlash between gear-rim and yaw drive pinions and to prevent the nacelle from oscillating due to the rotor rotation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] This operation however greatly reduces the reliability of the electric yaw drives, therefore the most common solution is the implementation of a hydraulically actuated disk brake.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The disc brake requires a flat circular brake disc and plurality of brake calipers with hydraulic pistons and brake pads Archived 2009-06-19 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The hydraulic yaw brakes are able to fix the nacelle in position thus relieving the yaw drives from that task.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The cost however of the yaw brake in combination with the requirement of a hydraulic installation (pump, valves, pistons) and its installation in the vicinity of brake pads sensitive to lubricant contamination is often an issue.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] A compromise that offers several advantages is the use of electric yaw brakes.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] These replace the hydraulic mechanism of the conventional brakes and with electro-mechanically actuated brake calipers.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The use of electric yaw brakes eliminates the complexity of the hydraulic leakages and the subsequent problems that these cause to the yaw brake operation.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Several wind turbine design and manufacturing companies experiment with alternative yaw breaking methods in order to eliminate the drawbacks of the existing systems and to reduce the cost of the system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] One of these alternatives involves the use of air pressure in order to achieve the necessary yaw braking moment.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] In this case, some of the gliding surface (usually the axial, due to higher available surface) is utilized in order to accommodate the yaw brake pads and the pneumatic brake mechanism.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The pneumatic actuator can be a conventional pneumatic cylinder or even a flexible air chamber which inflates when supplied with pressurized air.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Such a device is able to exert very high braking forces due to the high active surface.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] This is achieved with a simple industrial air pressure compression system (6–10 bar or 600–1,000 kPa or 87–145 psi) which is a reliable and low cost solution.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Furthermore, in the event of leakage, the environmental impact is practically zero compared to hydraulic oil leakages.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] Finally, brake actuators can be produced at very low cost from lightweight plastic materials thus significantly reducing the overall cost of the system.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The yaw vane (or tail fin) is a component of the yaw system used only on small wind turbines with passive yaw mechanisms.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] It is nothing more than a flat surface mounted on the nacelle by means of a long beam.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The combination of the large surface area of the fin and the increased length of the beam create a considerable torque which is able to rotate the nacelle despite the stabilizing gyroscopic effects of the rotor.
[src:wind-turbine-control/yaw-system] The required surface area however for a tail fin to be able to yaw a large wind turbine is enormous thus rendering the use of such a device un-economical.
